const e=JSON.parse(`[{"id":1,"number":1,"title":"God's Word Gives You Peace","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"As we become acquainted with the Bible we learn that there are principles to follow in studying God's word. Here are three:","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"Pray for Wisdom.","scripture":{"raw":"John 16:13; 1 Cor. 2:14","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":16,"verseStart":13},{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":2,"verseStart":14}]},"note":{"text":"\\"Spiritual things are spiritually discerned\\". Without the Holy Spirit to guide us we are as unable to discern the meaning of the scriptures, as one is to understand a foreign language without the use of an interpreter. Pray and ask the Holy Spirit to give you understanding and you will find rich meaning beyond your expectation."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"Compare relevant Bible passages.","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 24:25-27","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":24,"verseStart":25,"verseEnd":27}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus gave us an example when He gave a Bible study to the disciples and \\"explained to them what was said in all the Scriptures concerning Himself\\". Like a puzzle we need to fit in all the pieces in order to see the whole picture. We need to read everything the Bible has to say on any given subject not just a few verses here and there."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Open mind and willingness to obey.","scripture":{"raw":"Jeremiah 29:13","refs":[{"book":"Jeremiah","chapter":29,"verseStart":13}]},"note":{"text":"God will reveal Himself to those who realize that He has the best in store for them not to those who are reading the Bible in order to prove points or for mere curiosity. We will find him when we earnestly seek Him in order to know His will."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"How many of us are truly content with life? Ever since we're born we're never satisfied. There is in all of us a yearning for something more…"}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"quote","text":"There is a God-shaped vacuum in the heart of every man which only God can fill through His son, Jesus Christ.","attribution":"Blaise Pascal"}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"quote","text":"God made us, invented us as a man invents an engine. A car is made to run on petrol, and it would not run properly on anything else. Now God designed the human machine to run on Himself. He Himself is the fuel our spirits were designed to feed on. There is no other. God cannot give a happiness and peace apart from Himself.","attribution":"C. S. Lewis, Mere Christianity, p.90"}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"We are each born with a hole in our heart. We try to fill this void in our life with many different things; money, relationships, power, alcohol, materialism. But we soon find that these things do not fill us. It's like trying to shove a square peg into a round hole. It will never fit! The only thing that will truly fill us is a special relationship with the God of the universe. Nothing else!"}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What does Jesus promise to all who will come to Him?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt 11:28-30","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":11,"verseStart":28,"verseEnd":30}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What does Jesus want to give us?","scripture":{"raw":"John 14:27","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":27}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What does Jesus want us to do?","scripture":{"raw":"Phil. 4:6-7","refs":[{"book":"Philippians","chapter":4,"verseStart":6,"verseEnd":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"How does God give us His peace?","scripture":{"raw":"Colossians 1:20","refs":[{"book":"Colossians","chapter":1,"verseStart":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"Why is Jesus so important?","scripture":{"raw":"John 3:16-18; John 6:40; John 11:25, 26; John 20:31","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":3,"verseStart":16,"verseEnd":18},{"book":"John","chapter":6,"verseStart":40},{"book":"John","chapter":11,"verseStart":25,"verseEnd":26},{"book":"John","chapter":20,"verseStart":31}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Salvation is not a thing to be obtained. Salvation is a Person!!! And once you meet Him, nothing will change...\\nEXCEPT YOUR WHOLE LIFE!!\\nBecause of this we are going to spend the next few lessons getting to know Him better."}}],"pageCount":2},{"id":2,"number":2,"title":"Why We Need a Saviour","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Think about your life - did you ask for it? Did you pay for it? Did you exchange anything for it? No! It is a free gift from God. He had a plan for you from eternity ( ... you loved me before the creation of the world. John 17:24)\\n\\nAllow me to describe a scenario here: Imagine you are taking a bus ride. Suddenly the bus driver is involved in an accident. Did you cause the accident? No. Did you experience the accident? Yes. Were you impacted by the accident? Most definitely. When Adam sinned, you were impacted in a similar way as the passenger in the bus. Let's see how Adam's sin exactly impacted us personally and what solution God had ready even before it happened. Shall we?","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"Who created man and for what purpose?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 1:26","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":1,"verseStart":26}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What did God do after He formed man out of the dust of the ground?","scripture":{"raw":"Gen. 2:7","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":2,"verseStart":7}]},"note":{"text":"The word \\"life\\" in this text is in the plural form in the original Hebrew Bible. God breathed into man \\"the breath of lives.\\" This is because God created all men in that one man. That man was called Adam, which means mankind. According to the Bible, the whole of mankind is linked together by a common life and is considered a unit. The human race, to which we all belong, is the multiplication of Adam's one life. (See Acts 17:26)"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What was Adam not allowed to eat after God had placed him and his wife in the Garden of Eden?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 2:16, 17","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":2,"verseStart":16,"verseEnd":17}]},"note":{"text":"God created Adam and Eve with a free will. This tree was symbolic of the freedom God gave them. They were free to separate from Him at any time. And when they did separate from God, the Source of all life, there was much weeping in heaven for God knew the suffering, pain, devastation and death that would now be their fate."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Since all humanity was created in Adam, how many were affected by Adam's sin?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 5:12","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":5,"verseStart":12}]},"note":{"text":"When Adam sinned, he actually separated himself from God. And when he did this…his entire nature changed and became corrupted. Since we were still \\"in him\\" when he sinned…our natures through heredity changed as well."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What does David say about himself, which is also true of all of us?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 51:5","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":51,"verseStart":5}]},"note":{"text":"Sin is a condition or a nature that we all inherit from birth. It is something we are born with because of Adam's Fall. Therefore, we can do nothing to escape it, in and of ourselves. However, this is not our fault and God does not blame us for being born sinners."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What condition is ours from birth?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 58:3","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":58,"verseStart":3}]},"note":{"text":"We are born separated from God. But although we may be sinners from birth God has given us the choice to escape this problem through the gospel of Jesus Christ."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"Like sheep, in what two conditions do we sinners find ourselves?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 53:6","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":53,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"We are by nature self-centered. We can't help it! Let's say I mow the next door lady's lawn each week. Everyone would think that I was a \\"good\\" person but God looks at our heart. I could be doing this for several different reasons. I could be doing it because I enjoy being praised by others. I could be doing it because there is something I want from her and want to be in a good position to ask her for it. I could be in a bad family situation and need to get my 'strokes' somewhere. I might even be doing it because I heard that she's got quite a bit of money and one foot in the grave. We often don't realize why we're doing it! It's hidden deep in our heart or subconscious."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Why can't we trust our own hearts?","scripture":{"raw":"Jeremiah 17:9","refs":[{"book":"Jeremiah","chapter":17,"verseStart":9}]},"note":{"text":"Because our hearts are deceitful, we deceive ourselves into thinking that we are good; that we can save ourselves with God through our own good works. A good example of us being deceived by our own sinful hearts is Peter. Peter promised Jesus that he would rather die then betray Him and he really believed that of himself. He was very sincere. But when the test came he denied his Lord three times. (Mark 14:27-31)"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What does Jesus, the true Witness, say regarding our own self-evaluation?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 3:17","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":3,"verseStart":17}]},"note":{"text":"The problem with most of us is that we do not realize how sinful we are. We really have no understanding of our true condition. The problem is that we often compare ourselves with others to see how well we're doing. Let's say three of us were shooting arrows at a target in the sky. One may go up 75 ft. The other may go up only 8 ft and finally the third shot it up l50 ft. We'd say that #3 was the real winner but what if the target…was the sun! Would it really matter how far our arrows went up. We all fall miserably short of God's supreme standard."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What is the only thing that can truly set us free from our sin problem?","scripture":{"raw":"John 8:32","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":8,"verseStart":32}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"When we commit sin even against our wishes, what does it prove?","scripture":{"raw":"John 8:34","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":8,"verseStart":34}]},"note":{"text":"We are not sinful because we sin. We sin because we are sinners by nature. It's what we produce. An apple tree produces apples because it is an apple tree. We commit sins because we are sinful. It comes out of a natural tendency that we are all born with. Only God can take care of this for us."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"Freedom from sin's slavery is found only in whom?","scripture":{"raw":"John 8:36","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":8,"verseStart":36}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"Why did Jesus come into this world?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Timothy 1:15","refs":[{"book":"1 Timothy","chapter":1,"verseStart":15}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"What does the Bible have to say to those who claim \\"we have no sin\\"?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 1:8","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":1,"verseStart":8}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"Of what do we accuse God when we say that we have not sinned?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 1:10","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":1,"verseStart":10}]},"note":{"text":"The only reason that God's word tells us that we are sinners is to show us our need of a Saviour. Once we recognize our total sinfulness the gospel becomes the best good news we have ever heard."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":16,"text":"What are two things God does for us when we confess our sins to Him?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 1:9","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":1,"verseStart":9}]},"subParts":["a.","b."],"note":{"text":"The word forgiveness in this verse is translated from the Hebrew Original as: being separated from/sent away. Our sin has been forgiven already on the cross through Jesus Christ. God now longs for us to realize that and allow Him to separate us from sin and its burden."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"GOD IS NOT IN THE BUSINESS OF TRYING TO SEE HOW MANY PEOPLE HE CAN KEEP OUT OF HEAVEN. INSTEAD, BECAUSE OF HIS GREAT LOVE, HE HAS DONE EVERYTHING A GOD OF LOVE CAN DO TO SAVE EACH ONE OF US ETERNALLY.\\n\\nHIS SOLUTION FOR OUR SIN PROBLEM WAS HIS DEATH ON THE CROSS IN OUR PLACE. IN OUR NEXT LESSON WE SHALL EXAMINE JUST WHAT HAPPENED AT THE CROSS. WHY DID HE HAVE TO DIE? WHAT DID HE DO FOR THE ENTIRE WORLD THAT WE DON'T KNOW AND HOW DOES THAT AFFECT ME PERSONALLY?"}}],"pageCount":4},{"id":3,"number":3,"title":"How God Saved Us","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"In our last lesson we learnt that when Adam fell, we all fell. It is not our fault that we are born sinners. That's why God provided a \\"second Adam\\" (Jesus) to get us up again. We are in need of a Saviour because we cannot help ourselves. God did not leave us to ruin but devised a special plan where we could all be saved.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What are the consequences of sin?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:23","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":23}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"Evidently this principle of sin leading to death was so firmly entrenched in God's kingdom that He himself could not change it for us. If He could overlook the sin problem in us, how could He expect order and harmony in heaven? No, he devised a rescue mission for us and he appointed the apostle Paul to communicate it to us. The word gospel means good news. And when you discover what this gospel is you will agree that the gospel truly is good news.\\n\\nIn reading Paul's writings you will find a key phrase that runs all through his letters. That phrase is \\"in Christ\\" or \\"in Christ Jesus\\". Similar phrases such as \\"in Him\\" or \\"together with Him\\" or \\"in the Beloved\\" or \\"in whom\\" etc., all express the same idea. If we do not understand what the Bible means by this expression, \\"in Christ\\", we will never be able to fully understand the good news of the gospel."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"When did God devise this plan for us?","scripture":{"raw":"Ephesians 1:4, 5","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":1,"verseStart":4,"verseEnd":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What did God do?","scripture":{"raw":"Ephesians 2:4-6; Ephesians 1:9, 10","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":2,"verseStart":4,"verseEnd":6},{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":1,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"Death spread to all mankind because we were all \\"in Adam\\", so God devised a plan where we could all be saved \\"in Christ\\". The Father took the human race and corporately united it to His Son. But first Christ had to qualify to be our representative and saviour by consenting to be made human. God the Father united the life of His Son to our humanity in the womb of Mary. That is why Jesus is called the second or last Adam. It was the only way that He could represent us by consenting to be made like one of us. And when He died He took us all with Him (humanity through his birth) to meet the demands of our sins. His deeds of righteousness became our deeds of righteousness. We are legally redeemed."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"In order to save mankind, in whom did God put us?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Cor. 1:30","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":1,"verseStart":30}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What will happen to all who are in Christ?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Cor. 15:21, 22","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":15,"verseStart":21,"verseEnd":22}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"Through one man's sinful act what came to all men and what was the result?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 5:18 (first part)","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":5,"verseStart":18}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Through one Man's righteous act what came to all men and with what result?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 5:18 (last part)","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":5,"verseStart":18}]},"note":{"text":"Just as all die because all have sinned \\"in Adam,\\" so also all have obeyed \\"in Christ\\" and stand justified to life in Him. By His perfect life and sacrificial death He satisfied all the demands of the law on our behalf. In Christ, humanity has a new history that qualifies everybody for heaven who believes it.\\n\\nMany people believe salvation is just the forgiveness of sins. It's as though our sins are written on a blackboard and that when Jesus died He was like an eraser that erases all our sins. But this is not what the Bible teaches! Yes, our history or sins are written on a blackboard and Jesus is like an eraser but our slate does not remain empty. All of the good and holy and righteous deeds that Christ ever did is now transferred to us and are now written on our blackboard. This is the incredible good news of the gospel! But please notice that what God has brought to the whole human race by Christ's obedience is a free gift and it cannot be ours unless we receive it."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"At what point do we become included \\"in Christ\\"?","scripture":{"raw":"Ephesians 1:13, 14","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":1,"verseStart":13,"verseEnd":14}]},"note":{"text":"The moment you accept Christ as your Savior, and you trust only in Him for your salvation, God looks at you as accepted in the Beloved. It's as though once you're born you received a special birthday present from God. It's up to you as to when you open that gift and receive what He has given you."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What are the two options we have regarding this Gift of Life from God?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 5:12","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":5,"verseStart":12}]},"note":{"text":"If you refuse this gift you will not have eternal life no matter how many good works you have performed. If you accept and trust in Jesus as your salvation then the eternal life God offers to you in Christ is guaranteed!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What assurance does Paul give to those who believe in the Son of God?","scripture":{"raw":"Col.1:22","refs":[{"book":"Colossians","chapter":1,"verseStart":22}]},"note":{"text":"Though you may be a sinner, in God's eyes you are now considered perfect, blameless and without fault. This gives us peace with God and allows us to stop worrying about our salvation."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"If we believe in Jesus what do we become?","scripture":{"raw":"John 1:11-13","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":1,"verseStart":11,"verseEnd":13}]},"note":{"text":"If you believe in His name you have already received eternal life even though you may not feel it or think you deserve it. When President Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation it legally freed all slaves. Yet ten years later there were still some slaves working on plantations. Why? Because they did not believe the good news so to them they were not freed. When Jesus died on the cross He gave us ALL new life through Him. However if we do not believe this it will also not be true for us as well."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"If we hear and believe God's Word what will be the result?","scripture":{"raw":"John 5:24","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":5,"verseStart":24}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"What happens when you accept the gift of Christ's Righteousness?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Cor.5:17","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":5,"verseStart":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"What ministry does God give us?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Cor. 5:18-21","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":5,"verseStart":18,"verseEnd":21}]},"note":{"text":"God has given all of us a choice. We can either decide to be \\"in Adam\\" or \\"in Christ\\". There is no middle ground. It was not our fault that we were born \\"in Adam\\" but it is our fault if we decide not to be \\"in Christ\\"."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":16,"text":"What do you hear God pleading to you today?","scripture":{"raw":"Deuteronomy 30:19","refs":[{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":30,"verseStart":19}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"There is nothing we can do of ourselves to merit salvation. This comes to us only as a gift from God. God paid too high a price for us to ignore His incredible sacrifice for us. Why not receive this gift today?"}}],"pageCount":4},{"id":4,"number":4,"title":"God's Supreme Sacrifice For You","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"The Phoenicians (present day Lebanon) invented the cross approximately 600 years before Christ. It was then adopted by the Egyptians and later the Romans who refined it and used it to execute runaway slaves and their worst criminals.\\n\\nCrucifixion was the most painful and shameful instrument of execution ever practiced by man. The book, Watch With Me, gives a detailed description of Roman execution. It takes between three to seven days to die on the cross. Gangrene is formed in your hands and your feet where rusty nails have pierced. You have splitting migraine headaches. Every joint of your body feels torn apart and the pain is excruciating. You have cramps everywhere. Air is forced out of your lungs so that you are literarily suffocating without constantly raising your body up. In the night you were exposed to the cold, and in the daytime you were exposed to the heat and you were always crucified naked.\\n\\nBut what is it that makes Christ's death the supreme sacrifice above all other deaths? Many martyrs have suffered horrible deaths, some in ways that at least outwardly appear more agonizing than the death of the cross. In this lesson, we will explore these and other questions.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What did the chief priests and officers cry out when Pilate presented Christ to them?","scripture":{"raw":"John 19:5-7","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":19,"verseStart":5,"verseEnd":7}]},"note":{"text":"Pilate, who represented Rome, found no fault in Jesus, so the Jews had to give a reason why they were demanding Jesus' crucifixion. They said that they had a law that condemned Christ to death. The law they were referring to was the law of blasphemy."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"According to the law of blasphemy the Jews were referring to, what method of death was stipulated?","scripture":{"raw":"Leviticus 24:16","refs":[{"book":"Leviticus","chapter":24,"verseStart":16}]},"note":{"text":"In John 10:30-33, we see the Jews taking up stones again to stone Jesus when He said; \\"The Father and I are one\\". This proved they were aware that stoning was the method of death for blasphemy."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Why then did the Jews demand Christ be crucified, which to the Jews was synonymous to hanging on a tree? (see Acts 5:30; 10:39; 13:29)","scripture":{"raw":"Deuteronomy 21:22, 23","refs":[{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":21,"verseStart":22,"verseEnd":23}]},"note":{"text":"When the Jews cried out \\"crucify Him\\" they were not only demanding that Christ be put to death, but they were demanding that God's curse be upon Him. To a Jew when one is hung on a tree they could not offer a prayer of forgiveness for all the sins they committed because they were forever separated from God. They were accursed. This is what they wanted for Christ!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"How has Christ redeemed us?","scripture":{"raw":"Galatians 3:13","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":3,"verseStart":13}]},"note":{"text":"God made Christ to be a curse for us. He felt the guilt of the whole world."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"Did Jesus know that He would have to become a curse for us in order to save us?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 26:36-46","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":26,"verseStart":36,"verseEnd":46}]},"note":{"text":"God could not remove the curse from Christ because He loved us and that was the only way He could save us. \\"He spared not His own Son, but delivered Him up for us all.\\""}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Who raised Jesus from the dead?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 5:30; 1 Cor. 6:14; Gal. 1:1","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":5,"verseStart":30},{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":6,"verseStart":14},{"book":"Galatians","chapter":1,"verseStart":1}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus was totally dependent on His Father while in this world and He was no less dependent on the Father for His resurrection also."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What remarkable thing does Jesus exclaim upon His death?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 15:33-37","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":15,"verseStart":33,"verseEnd":37}]},"note":{"text":"The plan was that Jesus would die for the human race and then the Father would raise Him up. But, Jesus is crying out to His Father that He feels abandoned. What has gone wrong with the plan? Here is the point to the entire sacrifice right here...He feels that the offense of the sins of the whole world is too great for the Father to accept in His sacrifice. He does not feel his Father's presence any longer. The hope of the resurrection went with that abandonment. He could not save both the world and Himself. He had to choose between the world and Himself...AND HE STILL GOES THROUGH WITH IT!!!\\n\\nDo you know what He is saying in this act? That He loves us more than He loves Himself! That He was willing to die eternally without the hope of resurrection so that we could live. That He was willing to be eternally separated from His Father whom He had been together in fellowship with since the beginning of time. That He was willing to sacrifice never being able to see His Father's face again, in order that we would be saved. That is how much He loved us. This is the depth of His supreme sacrifice for us."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"In Psalm 22 we read the remarkable account of a crucifixion and the very words that Jesus uttered before He died. This account gives us a clue into the deep emotional pain that wracked His heart while on the cross."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"How does Jesus describe Himself in verse 6?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 22:6","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":22,"verseStart":6}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What has Christ done to show us the love of God?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 3:16","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":3,"verseStart":16}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus laid down His life and was willing to be blotted out of existence that we might live in His place. This is how much the cross demonstrated God's love for us sinners. By this supreme sacrifice Jesus was telling us sinners that He loves us more than Himself."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"How should this supreme sacrifice affect us?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 4:19; 2 Cor. 5:14, 15","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":4,"verseStart":19},{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":5,"verseStart":14,"verseEnd":15}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"When we see the love that Christ had in choosing us over Himself it awakens love in us. This is the right motivation for accepting Christ. Because He has shown us how much He loves us we can trust Him with our hearts and lives."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":5,"number":5,"title":"Faith - Jesus' and Mine","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"It was a sunny afternoon in Michigan when our daughter, then 4 years old, happily cycled on her bike while we walked next to her. I noticed that the rankling sound of the training wheels disappeared more and more. It was then that I asked her to stop for a minute, so I could secretly screw off one of her training wheels. The action went unnoticed and I signaled her to go on cycling. Ten minutes later I asked her if she had noticed that she was cycling with only one training wheel. She looked shocked and frightened, but after one glance at the back wheels she agreed, that she had indeed cycled with only one training wheel. I got bolder and popped the question: \\"Eliana, do you think that you can cycle with NO training wheels?\\" \\"Oh no! I will fall Daddy\\" was her response. I insisted that I thought she could and went on to take that last training wheel off. \\"But you must hold me, Daddy\\" Eliana insisted. So I counted: one, two, three and off she went, first I held her tiny waist, then I let go and she cycled, and cycled, turned around and came back to me proclaiming \\"I can do it! I am cycling without any training wheels\\".\\n\\nDid Eliana know she could do it? No. Who told her she could do it? Her Daddy did. Was she cycling on her faith? Or was she cycling on her Daddy's faith?\\n\\nIn the Bible we find many places that show that God has faith in you. Let's consider a few.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"How is faith described in the Word of God?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 11:1","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":11,"verseStart":1}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"How do we get faith?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 10:17","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":10,"verseStart":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Since faith works by love, let's find a few characteristics of love.","scripture":{"raw":"1 Cor. 13:7; 1 John 4:8","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":13,"verseStart":7},{"book":"1 John","chapter":4,"verseStart":8}]},"note":{"text":"In the love chapter of Corinthians we have a picture of what God is like. The word used here for love is agape and therefore Paul is making an observation rather than a standard that Christians should attain. Now read the verse again substituting \\"love\\" with \\"God\\". What a beautiful picture."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What does the faith of Jesus do?","scripture":{"raw":"Galatians 2:16","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":2,"verseStart":16}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"Who does the faith of Jesus go out to?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 3:22","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":3,"verseStart":22}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"How do I get faith?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 12:3; Hebrews 12:2","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":12,"verseStart":3},{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":12,"verseStart":2}]},"note":{"text":"Faith is a gift from God. It becomes more genuine as we spend time with Jesus."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"Do I need faith in order for God to work in my life?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 9:22,28,29","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":9,"verseStart":22},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":9,"verseStart":28,"verseEnd":29}]},"note":{"text":"Faith is the instrument by which the Holy Spirit transacts God's power in our lives. Without faith it is impossible for God to impart His forgiveness and transformation. \\"Do not wait to feel that you are made whole, but say, 'I believe it; it is so, not because I feel it, but because God has promised.'\\" Steps to Christ p.24.\\n\\nThe truth is that we don't work on our righteousness nor do we work on faith. Both are gifts. Both come as a result of knowing Jesus. And knowing Jesus comes as a result of spending time in prayer and communion with Him. If we will come to Him, He will supply to us His genuine faith that will work in us."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"How can we learn more about God?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 10:17; John 20:31; Philippians 4:6; Luke 11:9-13; Matthew 11:29","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":10,"verseStart":17},{"book":"John","chapter":20,"verseStart":31},{"book":"Philippians","chapter":4,"verseStart":6},{"book":"Luke","chapter":11,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":13},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":11,"verseStart":29}]},"subParts":["a. Listening to-- Romans 10:17, John 20:31","b. Talking to-- Philippians 4:6, Luke 11:9-13","c. Learning with -- Matthew 11:29"]}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"In Revelation 14:12 we read: \\"Here is the patience of the saints: here are they that keep the commandments of God, and the faith of Jesus.\\" This means that there are people that don't rely on their own faith but \\"keep Jesus' faith\\" who gives them His faith to live by. Don't you want to be one of them? Let's thank Him right now for His faithfulness and trust in us."}}],"pageCount":2},{"id":6,"number":6,"title":"The Second Adam","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Jesus was the epitome of righteousness on this earth. He lived a perfect life for you and me, not as an example alone, but as a substitute, a second Adam. Let's study how Jesus lived His life. What was the source of His power?","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"Was Jesus made to be like one of us in every way?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 2:14-18; Hebrews 10:5","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":2,"verseStart":14,"verseEnd":18},{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":10,"verseStart":5}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus was made like us in every way. He became just like one of us. He had struggles and temptations. He got hungry and thirsty and tired. He had to become like us so that He could qualify to become the second Adam, our Savior."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"If Jesus was like us in every way how did He perform the miracles He did and live obediently in every way?","scripture":{"raw":"John 5:19; John 6:57; John 8:28; John 14:8-11; John 10:30-33","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":5,"verseStart":19},{"book":"John","chapter":6,"verseStart":57},{"book":"John","chapter":8,"verseStart":28},{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":8,"verseEnd":11},{"book":"John","chapter":10,"verseStart":30,"verseEnd":33}]},"note":{"text":"The Son was in close connection with His Father and it was through this close union that the Father was able to work through Jesus. Jesus was completely dependent upon His Father in all things. The miracles, the healings, the teachings were all through the Father. Jesus became totally human and dependent upon heaven for His strength."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"How does this principle of union with the Father apply to us?","scripture":{"raw":"John 15:1-8","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":8}]},"note":{"text":"An apple tree bears fruit because it is an apple tree, never to become one. The same is true in the Christian life. A Christian does good because he is a Christian, never to become one. If we abide in Christ then Christ lives within us. \\"Sinful men can become righteous only as they have faith in God and maintain a vital connection with Him.\\" Desire of Ages p.309"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"How did Jesus maintain a vital connection with the Father?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 1:35","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":1,"verseStart":35}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What type of prayers did Jesus pray?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 26:39; John 6:38","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":26,"verseStart":39},{"book":"John","chapter":6,"verseStart":38}]},"note":{"text":"We can learn from Jesus in all things. Just as Jesus was surrendered to the Father, so are we to be surrendered to Jesus. \\"The proud heart strives to earn salvation; but both our title to heaven and our fitness for it are found in the righteousness of Christ. The Lord can do nothing toward the recovery of man until, convinced of his own weakness and stripped of all self-sufficiency, he yields himself to the control of God. Then he can receive the gift that God is waiting to bestow.\\" Desire of Ages, p. 300"}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"PRACTICAL PRAYER PRINCIPLES","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"A TIME OF PRAYER","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 1:35; Psalm 5:3","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":1,"verseStart":35},{"book":"Psalms","chapter":5,"verseStart":3}]},"note":{"text":"God enjoys having communion with Him throughout the day however if we do not turn to God in the beginning of our day for grace and strength we will often find ourselves on our knees in the evening asking for forgiveness for the mistakes we made because we neglected the great opportunity."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"A PLACE OF PRAYER","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 1:35; Matt. 6:6","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":1,"verseStart":35},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":6,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"It is important to find a special place where you will not be disturbed in your time with God. It may be a special chair by your bed or it may be somewhere in your back yard. My prayer life was re-charged when I decided to go outdoors in nature like Jesus did. Whether out on the deck in the morning or under the stars at night. I feel His presence more fully."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"A METHOD OF PRAYER","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 6:7, 8","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":6,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":8}]},"note":{"text":"Prayer is the opening up of your heart to God like a friend and is appropriate at any time, at any place, in any form. Yet in those special moments of aloneness, in intimate communion with His Father, Jesus knelt and prayed aloud."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"TO ABIDE IN JESUS IS TO ALLOW HIS WORDS TO ABIDE IN YOU","text":"In His analysis of how to live as a Christian, Jesus makes abundantly clear what it really means to be united with Him. \\"If you abide in Me, and My words abide in you, you will ask what you desire, and it shall be done for you.\\" John 15:7\\n\\nTo abide in Christ means that His words, His teachings, His life-giving principles fill your mind and transform your life. God's words contain life-giving power. This is the connection to the source of power in your life."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"Some read God's word and receive little benefit. Why?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 4:2","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":4,"verseStart":2}]},"note":{"text":"There are over 3,000 promises in the Bible. They are assurances from a loving heavenly Father of his care and concern. Accepting them by faith brings a peace and a calm assurance of his love and power in our lives. \\"It is faith that connects us with heaven, and brings us strength for coping with the powers of darkness. In Christ, God has provided means for subduing every sinful trait, and resisting every temptation, however strong. But many feel that they lack faith, and therefore they remain away from Christ. Let these souls, in their helpless unworthiness; cast themselves upon the mercy of their compassionate Savior. Look not to self, but to Christ. He who healed the sick and cast out demons when he walked among men is the same mighty Redeemer today. Faith comes by the word of God. Then grasp His promise, 'Whoever comes to Me I will never drive away.' John 6:37. Cast yourself at His feet with the cry, 'Lord, I believe; help my unbelief.' You can never perish while you do this; never!\\" Desire of Ages p.429"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"Without Christ what can we do on our own?","scripture":{"raw":"John 15:5","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"With Christ what can we do?","scripture":{"raw":"Phil. 4:13","refs":[{"book":"Philippians","chapter":4,"verseStart":13}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"What is the purpose of Christ's righteousness in us?","scripture":{"raw":"John 15:8; Psalm 23:3; Isaiah 61:3; Philippians 1:11","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":8},{"book":"Psalms","chapter":23,"verseStart":3},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":61,"verseStart":3},{"book":"Philippians","chapter":1,"verseStart":11}]},"note":{"text":"The glory that God is speaking of is not a self-centered egotistical kind of glory but rather one that results in blessings to others. Jesus said in John 12:32, \\"But I, when I am lifted up from the earth, will draw all men to myself.\\" It is not until God is lifted up and glorified that He can bring men to Himself for the purpose of salvation to mankind. His glory brings blessings to the world."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Just as a baby must receive nourishment through the umbilical cord in the womb of the mother, so we, too, receive nourishment through our vital connection with God. Without it we are powerless in our battle against evil. Without it we are helpless in our struggle against temptations and sin. Our works do not save us but they are the evidence of genuine faith in God in our lives. And they are instrumental in leading others to Christ and salvation."}}],"pageCount":4},{"id":7,"number":7,"title":"What Does the Bible Say About Conversion and Repentance?","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"When we realize our sin problem and our helplessness to rise above our natures on our own there is only one thing left to do. To give up and let God take control! When God brings us up to this point we consider the miracle of conversion. But what about repentance? Don't we have to repent first to come to God? Doesn't repentance come before conversion? In this lesson we will explore what the Bible teaches about conversion and repentance.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"How important is the experience of conversion?","scripture":{"raw":"John 3:3","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":3,"verseStart":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"Where does the power for the new birth come from?","scripture":{"raw":"John 1:12, 13","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":1,"verseStart":12,"verseEnd":13}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Who is the active agent in the new birth?","scripture":{"raw":"John 3:5; Titus 3:5","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":3,"verseStart":5},{"book":"Titus","chapter":3,"verseStart":5}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"Conversion is a supernatural work of the Holy Spirit. It is marked by a change of attitude toward God. Instead of running away from God the one who is being converted turns toward God."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Does mankind naturally understand spiritual things?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Cor. 2:14, Romans 8:7","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":2,"verseStart":14},{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"So what must take place in order for us to understand?","scripture":{"raw":"Ephesians 4:23, 24","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":4,"verseStart":23,"verseEnd":24}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"Conversion creates a new and deeper capacity for knowing God. The Holy Spirit renews your mind and thereby creates new understandings and interests that were not there before. You begin to experience a new desire to know God."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Does the new heart lead to a changed life?","scripture":{"raw":"Ezekiel 36:26, 27","refs":[{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":36,"verseStart":26,"verseEnd":27}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"Conversion is called the new birth. It's the beginning of spiritual life. Just as you cannot choose your own birthday in the physical life, you cannot choose your own spiritual birthday. You cannot convert yourself. Or others for that matter. That is completely up to God. You can share Christ with others but it is up to the Holy Spirit to change the attitude toward God."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What promise does God make about the work He starts in us?","scripture":{"raw":"Phil 1:6","refs":[{"book":"Philippians","chapter":1,"verseStart":6}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Is repentance necessary for salvation?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 13:3; 2 Peter 3:9","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":13,"verseStart":3},{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":3,"verseStart":9}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What types of people feel the need for repentance?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 2:17","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":2,"verseStart":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"Is there a genuine and a false sorrow for sin?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Corinthians 7:10","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":7,"verseStart":10}]},"note":{"text":"Genuine sorrow for sin includes a turning away from the sin. The false sorrow for sin is more of a sorrow for the consequences of the sin. The thief is not sorry he stole but only sorry that he got caught and is now in jail."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"So where does genuine repentance come from?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 5:31","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":5,"verseStart":31}]},"note":{"text":"\\"Just here is a point on which many may err, and hence they fail of receiving the help that Christ desires to give them. They think that they cannot come to Christ unless they first repent, and that repentance prepares for the forgiveness of their sins.... The Bible does not teach that the sinner must repent before he can heed the invitation of Christ.... We can no more repent without the Spirit of Christ to awaken the conscience than we can be pardoned without Christ.\\" Steps to Christ p. 26.\\n\\nHow is repentance accomplished? Do we come to Christ in order to repent, or do we repent in order to come to Christ? We cannot repent of anything UNTIL we come to Christ. Repentance is something we receive. It is a gift from God. We come to Jesus and He grants us repentance and then forgives our sins. We do not cleanse ourselves in order to come to Christ. Instead we come to Christ and then HE does the job of cleansing us."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How does God lead us to repentance?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 2:4","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":2,"verseStart":4}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"After Peter denied Jesus and then remembered His goodness, what did He do?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 26:74, 75","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":26,"verseStart":74,"verseEnd":75}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"We cannot turn away from sin in our own strength but we can seek the Lord to do those things for us. God delights to help those who cannot help themselves. We don't turn away from sins in order to repent. We come to Jesus in order to repent. Our part is only always to come to Him."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":8,"number":8,"title":"Surrender","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"As we perceive that God is real and active in our lives we have a desire to learn more about Him. As we begin to sense our sinfulness and our need for Christ we begin to desire a personal relationship with Him. We want to give Him our love but sometimes there seems to be nothing there. How does this work of conversion begin and what is my role in it? We shall see more clearly as we begin our study on surrender.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What type of righteousness is needed for salvation?","scripture":{"raw":"Gal. 2:15,16, 21","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":2,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":16},{"book":"Galatians","chapter":2,"verseStart":21}]},"note":{"text":"Righteousness by faith is a transaction. The greatest trade that was ever made! We trade our total sinfulness in exchange for Christ's holy righteousness. This is the only righteousness that can gain us entrance into heaven. We receive this righteousness of Christ when we give up on trying to obtain salvation by our good works or behavior."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What does the Bible call those who have given up on themselves?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:2","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":2}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Do dead people sin?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:7","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"How is the sinner put to death?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:6","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"There are a number of ways that one could kill themselves if they wished. You could shoot yourself with a gun, take pills, etc. but no one can kill themselves by crucifying himself. And it's the same way with surrender. Someone else has to do that for us. That someone is God. But because He is a gentleman He does not force Himself or posses us against our will. He asks us permission first. Rev. 3:20"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"How did Jesus speak of self-surrender?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 16:24-26","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":16,"verseStart":24,"verseEnd":26}]},"note":{"text":"We all have to die! Our choice is whether we want to die to self and be reborn in Christ or to die without Christ and forfeit our salvation. The more we hold on to the control of our lives here on earth we lose our eternal life but when we decide to lose it for the sake of Christ… we gain eternal life!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Is self-surrender a one time experience?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 9:23","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":9,"verseStart":23}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"Is there life after spiritual death?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:4, 5","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":4,"verseEnd":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Who is it that controls the new life?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:13","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":13}]},"note":{"text":"An instrument is totally controlled by another. Surrendering, or giving up is admitting that we can do nothing. Inevitably, therefore, the work of bringing us to the point of surrender must be the work of God. It is not something we can do for ourselves."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What choice do we have as to who is in control of our lives?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:16; Luke 11:23, James 4:4","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":16},{"book":"Luke","chapter":11,"verseStart":23},{"book":"James","chapter":4,"verseStart":4}]},"note":{"text":"We are controlled by either God or Satan! The only control we have is to choose who is going to control us. \\"Unless we do yield ourselves to the control of Christ, we shall be dominated by the wicked one. We must inevitably be under the control of the one or the other of the two great powers that are contending for the supremacy of the world. It is not necessary for us deliberately to choose the service of the kingdom of darkness in order to come under its dominion. We have only to neglect to ally ourselves with the kingdom of light\\" DA 324"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"How do we resist the Devil and his control?","scripture":{"raw":"James 4:7-8","refs":[{"book":"James","chapter":4,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":8}]},"note":{"text":"Submit and draw near to God. Let God fight against Satan in your behalf. You are not strong enough on your own."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"Aren't we supposed to use our will and will power to do good?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 7:18-19","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":7,"verseStart":18,"verseEnd":19}]},"note":{"text":"\\"Everything depends on the right action of the will. The power of choice God has given to men; it is theirs to exercise. You cannot change your heart, you cannot of yourself give to God its affections; but you can choose to serve Him. You can give Him your will; He will then work in you to will and to do according to His good pleasure. Thus your whole nature will be brought under the control of the Spirit of Christ; your affections will be centered on Him, your thoughts will be in harmony with Him.\\" Steps to Christ p.30"}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Instead of wasting our time in good works we need to re-channel those energies into spending time with Christ. As we make the choice to spend time day by day in beholding Christ, as we invite Him to do His work in our lives, He will lead us step by step to the point of surrender. Giving up is possible only when He has brought us up to that point."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":9,"number":9,"title":"Growing in Christ","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Are you interested in growing spiritually? You cannot grow by focusing on growth. Probably nothing is more detrimental to spiritual growth than to be constantly checking yourself for fruit. Is your goal to reach the \\"measure of the stature of the fullness of Christ\\"? (Eph. 4:13) Do you sometimes wonder whether you are growing at all? There's one sure way to tell. Look at whether you are eating. Isn't the way to grow spiritually to partake of the Bread of Life? In this lesson we shall learn how to grow in our Christian journey. Are we to depend on Christ for salvation and then on our own works thereafter? What does God expect of me? What part of the process does God play and what part do I play?","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What is the growth in the Christian life?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Peter 3:18","refs":[{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":3,"verseStart":18}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"Where do we obtain this grace?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 4:16","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":4,"verseStart":16}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Where do we obtain the knowledge of Jesus Christ?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Peter 2:2, 3","refs":[{"book":"1 Peter","chapter":2,"verseStart":2,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"It is through personal study of the Word that we come to a fuller understanding of the knowledge of Jesus."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What is it that needs to grow?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Thessalonians 1:3","refs":[{"book":"2 Thessalonians","chapter":1,"verseStart":3}]},"note":{"text":"Another word for faith is trust. Our trust in God must grow in its constancy of dependence on God. Peter was a good example of our situation. At one point his eyes are only on Jesus as he gets out of the boat and onto the water to be with Him but once he takes his eyes off Christ and begins to depend back on himself …he begins to sink. It's not unusual for us to waver like this in our faith as well."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What is necessary to grow and bear fruit?","scripture":{"raw":"John 15:4","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":4}]},"note":{"text":"Growth in the Christian life is learning to depend upon God more and more. Dependence upon God is an all or nothing proposition. There is no such thing as a partial trust or partial surrender. You are either surrendered to God at any given moment or you are not surrendered to Him and are depending upon yourself."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Will Christ ever separate from us?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 8:35, 38-39","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":35},{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":38,"verseEnd":39}]},"note":{"text":"Nothing can separate us from the love of God, therefore, if we fall and fail we don't need to wait for God to \\"cool off\\". We don't give up and decide that we'll never make it to heaven. We don't try to \\"make things right\\" on our own and then come back to Him. We come to Him immediately, confess our sin and our need of Him. Through it all, our relationship with God continues."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"But is it possible for us to separate from Christ?","scripture":{"raw":"John 15:6","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"God will NEVER separate from us therefore the only time separation occurs is when it's us doing the separating."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Are we naturally strong or weak?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 26:41","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":26,"verseStart":41}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"How do we grow strong?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Corinthians 12:9,10","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":12,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"We realize that as Christians we don't grow by becoming stronger and stronger. We grow by realizing anew each day how weak we are and how dependent we are upon God's grace."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"How am I to stay connected with Christ?","scripture":{"raw":"Col. 2:6","refs":[{"book":"Colossians","chapter":2,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"\\"Do you ask, 'How am I to abide in Christ?' In the same way as you received Him at first…you gave yourself to God, to be His wholly, to serve and obey Him, and you took Christ as your Savior. You could not yourself atone for your sins or change your heart; but having given yourself to God; you believe that He for Christ's sake did all this for you. By faith you became Christ's and by faith you are to grow up in Him—by giving and taking. You are to give all—your heart, your will, your service—give yourself to Him to obey all His requirements; and you must take all—Christ, the fullness of all blessing, to abide in your heart, to be your strength, your righteousness, your everlasting helper—to give you power to obey.\\" Steps to Christ, p. 34"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What is the secret to Christian growth?","scripture":{"raw":"Heb. 12:2, 3","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":12,"verseStart":2,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"\\"When the mind dwells upon self, it is turned away from Christ, the source of strength and life. Hence it is Satan's constant effort to keep the attention diverted from the Savior and thus prevents the union and communion of the soul with Christ. The pleasures of the world, life's cares and perplexities and sorrows, the faults of others, or our own faults and imperfections—to any or all of these he will seek to divert the mind.\\" Steps to Christ, p. 34"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"What will happen when we stay focused on Jesus?","scripture":{"raw":"John 15:5; Phil. 4:13","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":5},{"book":"Philippians","chapter":4,"verseStart":13}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Many people have the mistaken idea that spiritual birth comes from God but that spiritual growth is their own responsibility. It is simply not possible to grow in grace by our own feeble efforts. Growth is a gift from God. And we continue to receive this gift as we ask Him into our lives each day.\\n\\nWhen God invites us to a place of complete dependence upon Him, when He asks us to acknowledge our helplessness apart from Him, He is not opening up the door for inactivity. The life controlled by God is the life of highest usefulness and service. Through Christ we can do all things."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":10,"number":10,"title":"The Second Coming of Christ","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Each year we celebrate the birth of Christ at Christmas. It's a time of joy and reflection. But did you know that for every prophecy on the first coming of Christ in the Old Testament, there are eight on the second coming? The Bible mentions Jesus' return over 1,500 times. The return of our Lord is mentioned once in every five verses in the New Testament. That's how important it is! It was a favorite theme of Jesus and He spoke of it quite often. In today's lesson we will explore what the Bible teaches about this incredible event: the coming of Christ.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What promise did Jesus give to His disciples concerning His return?","scripture":{"raw":"John 14:1-3","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What did Jesus say He would do when he returns?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 16:27","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":16,"verseStart":27}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"In what manner does the Bible teach that Jesus will come?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev 1:7; Acts 1:9-11","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":1,"verseStart":7},{"book":"Acts","chapter":1,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":11}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Will His coming be a secret and silent event?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 50:3, 4","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":50,"verseStart":3,"verseEnd":4}]},"note":{"text":"His coming will not be in secret. The Bible teaches that everyone will know that this climactic event is taking place. It will be a very real, visible and audible event!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What will the angels be doing at this time?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 24:30, 31; Matthew 25:31","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":30,"verseEnd":31},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":25,"verseStart":31}]},"note":{"text":"When one angel rolled back the stone from Christ's tomb, the Roman soldiers became as dead men, dazed by the angel's countenance, which was \\"like lightening\\" (Matt. 28:2,3). Think of the splendor of \\"ten thousand times ten thousand, and thousands of thousands\\" (Rev. 5:11) of angels coming with Christ!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What will happen to those who are 'in Christ' at the time of His coming?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Thess. 4:16, 17","refs":[{"book":"1 Thessalonians","chapter":4,"verseStart":16,"verseEnd":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What will those who are not 'in Christ' be doing at this time?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 6:15-17","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":17}]},"note":{"text":"This is one of the saddest pictures in the Bible. A people who deliberately and continually reject the One who loves them so and now finally realize that they are lost. How sad when it could have been so different."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What will happen to our bodies when Christ returns?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Cor. 15:51-54","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":15,"verseStart":51,"verseEnd":54}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"The coming of our Lord will not be a secret event but rather the most incredible event that the world has ever seen. For some it will be a most wonderful event and for others it will be terrifying. God wants us all to be in heaven with Him but He cannot force those that refuse Him. And He cannot bring those along that don't want to be there. Never again can He risk the harmony of heaven again."}}],"pageCount":2},{"id":11,"number":11,"title":"Signs of Christ's 2nd Coming","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"In the last lesson we studied the way in which Christ will appear. We learned that it will not be a secret event but that every eye will see Him. We learned that He will descend from heaven with all His angels and with the sound of a loud trumpet. We saw that the dead in Christ will rise and that we who were alive will meet Him in the clouds. But when will these things appear? How close are we to this climactic event? In this lesson we will study the prophecies of Jesus concerning His return. After all, who could know more about the end of the world than the One who created it in the first place?","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"How did the disciples know that Christ would come back to our world a second time?","scripture":{"raw":"John 14:1-3","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What question did the disciples ask concerning this?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 24:3","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":3}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus answered clearly and positively. In chapter 24 of Matthew and chapter 21 of Luke He gave several signs or evidences by which we can know when His coming is near. Other Bible prophesies help fill out the picture, detailing world conditions just before Christ's return. As we will see, these prophecies are being fulfilled before our very eyes; they indicate that Christ's coming is near at hand."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"SIGNS IN THE NATURAL WORLD","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What will be the signs in the natural world?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt 24:7; Luke 21:11; Luke 21:25","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":7},{"book":"Luke","chapter":21,"verseStart":11},{"book":"Luke","chapter":21,"verseStart":25}]},"note":{"text":"The word \\"pestilence\\" refers to a deadly epidemic plague. The country of Africa is dying off in mass epidemic proportions due to the deadly AIDS virus and the avian \\"bird\\" flu has already begun to hit some parts of the world. Earthquakes, hurricanes, tsunami's and other natural disasters have quadrupled since 1950. Jesus' predictions are rapidly being fulfilled."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"SIGNS IN THE SOCIAL WORLD","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What will be the signs in the social world?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Tim. 3:1-5; Matt. 24:12; Matt. 24:37-39","refs":[{"book":"2 Timothy","chapter":3,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":5},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":12},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":37,"verseEnd":39}]},"note":{"text":"The moral decay of our world is staggering. We are in the midst of a moral crisis. New lifestyle alternatives are replacing what was once known as sin. Marriage is no longer honored. Child abuse and molestation has skyrocketed. Violence and crime are commonplace. People are killing children in our schools. Suicide is at an all-time high. Drug use is out of control. And sex is becoming the essence of entertainment in this country. Another prophecy is being fulfilled."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"SIGNS IN THE ECONOMIC WORLD","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What are the signs in the economic world?","scripture":{"raw":"James 5:1-5","refs":[{"book":"James","chapter":5,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":5}]},"note":{"text":"Greed and materialism marks the days just before an economic collapse. The love of comfort and luxury are the hallmarks of this society. In the U.S. people are focused on accumulating wealth and in collecting as many toys as they can for themselves. This is indicative of a society that is rich in attitude toward money (careers, power, status) and poor toward God."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"SIGNS IN THE POLITICAL WORLD","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What are the signs in the political world?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 13:7, 8; Luke 21:9, 10","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":13,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":8},{"book":"Luke","chapter":21,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"Before the twentieth century, war had never been waged on a truly worldwide scale. But in this century nearly every significant nation on earth joined in two great global conflicts. And though everyone values peace and talks it up; yet everyone keeps falling into armed conflicts. At any one moment there are no less than a dozen military exchanges somewhere in the world today. And fear over nuclear armament is always prevailing. Yes, Christ predicted our state years before it happened."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"SIGNS IN THE SUPERNATURAL WORLD","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What are the signs in the spiritual world?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Thess. 2:9; Matt. 24:23-27; 1 Tim. 4:1; Rev. 16:14","refs":[{"book":"2 Thessalonians","chapter":2,"verseStart":9},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":23,"verseEnd":27},{"book":"1 Timothy","chapter":4,"verseStart":1},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":16,"verseStart":14}]},"note":{"text":"These passages indicate that toward the end of time that the antichrist will feature all kinds of miracles and signs, a counterfeit manifestation of the supernatural. The occult is alive and well and on the rise. Psychics sell their 'gifts' on infomercials; witches and warlocks appear on talk shows. New-Agers are everywhere; selling magical crystals and channeling departed spirits. All this makes it even clearer that history is moving toward a climax."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"SIGNS IN THE CULTURAL WORLD","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What are the signs in the cultural world?","scripture":{"raw":"Daniel 12:4","refs":[{"book":"Daniel","chapter":12,"verseStart":4}]},"note":{"text":"Daniel here indicates that knowledge of his prophecies would increase 'in the time of the end'. But the language used in this prediction also seems to point straight toward our computerized information age. Knowledge of all kinds has increased at lightning speed these past few years. Before 1850, people moved around by horse and buggy pretty much as they had from the beginning of time. Now we break the sound barrier and span the globe in everything from Concorde airplanes to space shuttles. Increased travel and the recent flood of inventions suggests a fulfillment of this prophecy and gives further evidence that we are living in 'the time of the end'."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"heading","title":"SIGNS IN THE RELIGIOUS WORLD","text":""}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What are the signs in the religious world?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 24:14; Joel 2:28, 29","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":14},{"book":"Joel","chapter":2,"verseStart":28,"verseEnd":29}]},"note":{"text":"The Bible predicts that just before the return of Christ that the Holy Spirit would direct many to knowledge of Christ. As a result the gospel will be preached to the whole world. Technology has now made it possible for all to hear the gospel through communication systems. This prediction is still in the process of coming true."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"Why is it important not to pinpoint dates?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 24:36","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":36}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"Of what great danger does Christ solemnly warn?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 21:29-34","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":21,"verseStart":29,"verseEnd":34}]},"note":{"text":"There is great danger in becoming so busy with the cares of this life that we neglect the most important thing in life: a relationship with the God of the universe who is planning to return very soon."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How can I be certain to be ready when Jesus comes back?","scripture":{"raw":"John 1:12; John 6:37; Rev. 3:20","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":1,"verseStart":12},{"book":"John","chapter":6,"verseStart":37},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":3,"verseStart":20}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Through the Holy Spirit, Jesus knocks and asks to come into my heart so that He can change my life. If I unreservedly turn my life over to Him, He will not only erase all my sins of the past and replace my sins with all His acts of righteousness but He also gives me the power to live a godly life. As a free gift, He bestows upon me His own righteous character so that doing His will becomes a pleasure. It is so simple that many doubt it is reality. But it's true. My part is simply to give my life to Christ and let Him live within me. His part is to work the mighty miracle with me that changes my life and prepares me for His second coming. It is a free gift. I need only to accept it."}}],"pageCount":4},{"id":12,"number":12,"title":"The State of the Dead","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"When a man dies, what becomes of him? We know something of life and what it is and means. But what in the world happens to us when we die? Where do we go? Heaven? Hell? Purgatory? Limbo? What awaits us in the shadows ahead? What about our dead loved ones? Since we know that the Bible is the word of God shouldn't we turn to the one dependable source of information? The Bible's teaching on death is consistent, not confusing. There may be some surprises. But its answers are reasonable, satisfying and best of all, comforting.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"How did Jesus refer to death?","scripture":{"raw":"John 11:11-14","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":11,"verseStart":11,"verseEnd":14}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"How does the Old Testament refer to death?","scripture":{"raw":"Deuteronomy 31:14-16; 2 Sam. 7:12","refs":[{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":31,"verseStart":14,"verseEnd":16},{"book":"2 Samuel","chapter":7,"verseStart":12}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"How did Paul understand the condition of death concerning the resurrection?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Thess. 4:15, 16; 1 Cor. 15:51-54; Acts 13:36","refs":[{"book":"1 Thessalonians","chapter":4,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":16},{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":15,"verseStart":51,"verseEnd":54},{"book":"Acts","chapter":13,"verseStart":36}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What about Daniel in the Old Testament? How did he understand death and the resurrection?","scripture":{"raw":"Daniel 12:2","refs":[{"book":"Daniel","chapter":12,"verseStart":2}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What did Jesus teach regarding death and the resurrection?","scripture":{"raw":"John 5:28, 29","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":5,"verseStart":28,"verseEnd":29}]},"note":{"text":"The Bible describes death to sleep over 50 times. In order to understand the condition of death or 'sleep/rest' we must first understand the condition of life."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What two elements did God combine to make man a living soul?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 2:7","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":2,"verseStart":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"How is the process God used in creating a soul reversed when we die?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 104:29","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":104,"verseStart":29}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Can a soul die?","scripture":{"raw":"Ezekiel 18:20","refs":[{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":18,"verseStart":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"When life ends, what is left?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 3:19","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":3,"verseStart":19}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"How does the Bible define \\"life\\"?","scripture":{"raw":"Job 27:3","refs":[{"book":"Job","chapter":27,"verseStart":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What happens when the breath returns to God?","scripture":{"raw":"Job 14:10-12","refs":[{"book":"Job","chapter":14,"verseStart":10,"verseEnd":12}]},"note":{"text":"God did not put a living soul into Adam. Adam became a living soul as a result of the combination of the body plus the breath or spirit from God. When a light bulb is connected to electricity, we get light. No one puts the light in the bulb. It is the result of uniting those two components. When we take away the electricity, the light ceases to exist. According to the Bible, the soul is a combination of body plus breath, or spirit. When the breath or 'spirit' of God departs from the body, the soul ceases to exist.\\n\\nDUST + BREATH = SOUL\\nSOUL - BREATH = DUST"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How much does man know during the time that he is dead?","scripture":{"raw":"Eccl. 9:5,6, 10","refs":[{"book":"Ecclesiastes","chapter":9,"verseStart":5,"verseEnd":6},{"book":"Ecclesiastes","chapter":9,"verseStart":10}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"Can the dead praise God?","scripture":{"raw":"Ps. 115:17","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":115,"verseStart":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"Can a dead person return to his house as a 'departed spirit' ghost?","scripture":{"raw":"Job 7:9,10","refs":[{"book":"Job","chapter":7,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"As we have studied earlier, many demons can produce miracles not least of which is impersonating dead loved ones. The story is told of an evangelist who preached on the state of death. Afterwards one of the people in the audience had an \\"appearing\\" of their wife who had died earlier. She had the same voice and mannerism of his wife. Convinced of this Bible teaching, he told his \\"wife\\" to leave in the name of Jesus Christ and she disappeared and turned into a demon. There is truth only in God's word."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"So when a man dies he does not live somewhere else. He is not in heaven, not in hell, not in purgatory. He is not alive at all, anywhere, in any condition. He is in a state of sleep or unconsciousness. The dead rest quietly in their graves until Jesus comes. And when we stop to think it through, how could this be improved upon? As always, God has arranged what is best. Instead of permitting the departed one to look down from heaven and see the distress and grief his departing has caused; instead of allowing a departed husband or wife to see his spouse quickly transfer his love to another; instead of permitting parents to witness their children suffering through problems, Jesus has arranged death to be a short period of unconscious sleep. There is no hardship on the departed one, for they are not conscious of passing time. They fall asleep and the next moment (so it seems) they awake and are reunited with their loved ones and Jesus."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":13,"number":13,"title":"The Truth About Hell","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"From the beginning of sin it has been the work of the devil to misrepresent the true character of God. In heaven he injected doubt into the minds of the angels as to the justice and love of God. In this work of deception he finally succeeded so well that one third of the angels followed him into rebellion. (Rev. 12:3, 4, 7-9)\\n\\nSince his expulsion from heaven it has been the devil's studied purpose to bring havoc and confusion to the earth. He seeks to alienate the affections of God's children by misrepresenting the character of God. He has confused even those who profess to be Christians. They reason that if God is a God of love, how can he permit people to be tormented forever? We'll explore the Bibles' teachings on hell.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"For whom was 'hell' prepared?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 25:41","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":25,"verseStart":41}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"When does Christ reward each man according to what he has chosen?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 16:27","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":16,"verseStart":27}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"How will Christ classify those at the time of His coming?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 25:31-34","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":25,"verseStart":31,"verseEnd":34}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"readDirective","text":"PLEASE READ: Matthew 13:24-30; 36-43.\\nIn this parable Christ outlines the fate of the wicked and the reward of the righteous in detail."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"In His parable, when did Jesus indicate that the harvest, or the separation of the evil from the good, would take place?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 13:39","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":13,"verseStart":39}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"In the parable, when will the wicked, or the tares, be destroyed?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 13:40","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":13,"verseStart":40}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"When will Christ send forth His angels to separate the good from the evil?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 24:30, 31","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":30,"verseEnd":31}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What will not happen to those who believe in God?","scripture":{"raw":"John 3:16","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":3,"verseStart":16}]},"note":{"text":"This text does not say that the sinner will live forever in torment. Life and death are contrasted here, showing that the wicked will cease to live while those who have accepted the gift of God will continue to live forever."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What does God call the death that is the final separation from God for the wicked?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 20:6, 14","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":6},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":14}]},"note":{"text":"Wrath is also translated as: separation from God. Away from God there is no way we can exist. He is life and separated from God there is no life."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What is the wages (or consequences) of sin according to the Bible?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:23","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":23}]},"note":{"text":"The wages of sin is death not eternally burning hell. It is the opposite of eternal life."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"How complete will the destruction of the wicked be?","scripture":{"raw":"Malachi 4:1","refs":[{"book":"Malachi","chapter":4,"verseStart":1}]},"note":{"text":"Death is not an active punishment from God. When the unbeliever sees Christ on His throne, he realizes that God truly is just, merciful and kind. The beauty that surrounds the Godhead is too powerful for the unbeliever to stand--it kills him."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"Do the following verses indicate that the wicked will be continually burning?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 21:9; Psalm 37:10, 20, 36; Psalm 145:20","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":21,"verseStart":9},{"book":"Psalms","chapter":37,"verseStart":10},{"book":"Psalms","chapter":37,"verseStart":20},{"book":"Psalms","chapter":37,"verseStart":36},{"book":"Psalms","chapter":145,"verseStart":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How does God describe the effect of the fire that will be used on the wicked?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 25:41","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":25,"verseStart":41}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"What kind of fire did God use in the destruction of Sodom and Gomorrah?","scripture":{"raw":"Jude 7","refs":[{"book":"Jude","chapter":1,"verseStart":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"How did God compare what happened to Sodom and Gomorrah with what happens to the ungodly?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Peter 2:6","refs":[{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":2,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"Sodom and Gomorrah are not still burning today. They have been burnt to ashes long ago. It is the effect or result of the fire that is everlasting or eternal not the punishment in itself. Once you are destroyed by fire it is final!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"What else will be destroyed or purified by this fire besides the wicked?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Peter 3:10","refs":[{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":3,"verseStart":10}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":16,"text":"How does God feel about the death of those who refuse salvation?","scripture":{"raw":"Ezekiel 33:11","refs":[{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":33,"verseStart":11}]},"note":{"text":"God must remove sin once and for all from the universe. If sin were allowed to continue, it would contaminate the entire universe. And that's what got us into this mess to begin with."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":17,"text":"How many individuals does God want to see perish in hell?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Peter 3:9","refs":[{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":3,"verseStart":9}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":18,"text":"What choice does God offer to every person on this earth?","scripture":{"raw":"Deut. 30:19, 20","refs":[{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":30,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":20}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"God is definitely not in the business of tormenting people. He doesn't want to see any of the children He created lost but unfortunately those that reject Him don't give Him any choice. He cannot put the entire universe at risk ever again. He is a God of love. He will miss every single soul that is lost for eternity."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":14,"number":14,"title":"Satan's Time Out - The Millennium","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"God can't wait to finally end the pain and suffering of sin and set up His eternal kingdom of love and freedom. God will send Jesus back again to the earth. This time instead of coming in humility and rejection, He comes in power and great glory to gather His people, those who lay in dusty graves along with those who are still alive and take them home to be with Him forever. But let's focus back on the earth and discover what effect Christ's fiery entry will have on our planet.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What will happen to those who are 'in Christ' (both dead and living) when Jesus comes?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Thess 4:17","refs":[{"book":"1 Thessalonians","chapter":4,"verseStart":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What happens to those who are still alive who reject Christ when He comes?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Thess 2:8; Jeremiah 25:33","refs":[{"book":"2 Thessalonians","chapter":2,"verseStart":8},{"book":"Jeremiah","chapter":25,"verseStart":33}]},"note":{"text":"The unbelievers will not be able to stand because sin, which they have chosen to retain by rejecting the gift of God, salvation in Jesus Christ, cannot stand before a holy God. Christ will not come veiled in His humanity; He will come in glorious divinity. Hebrews 12:29 say He is a consuming fire and the unbelievers will be destroyed by the brightness of His coming."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What is the condition of the earth following Christ's return?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Peter 3:10; Isaiah 24:3-6","refs":[{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":3,"verseStart":10},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":24,"verseStart":3,"verseEnd":6}]},"note":{"text":"The earth will be devoid of any living thing. The entire atmosphere is gone, its elements destroyed by the blazing fire of Christ's coming. But the final destruction of sin and sinners is still to come because God says \\"I will not destroy it completely\\" (Jeremiah 4:27) this is only Phase I in the setting up of His kingdom."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What happens to Satan at the time of Christ's coming?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 20:1-3","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"The word \\"abyss\\" is the same Greek word as the word \\"deep\\" in Genesis 1:2. The earth will be in the same condition as when God began His creation. It will be dark and empty. God puts Satan and his angels in a major 'time out' for a thousand years. He is forced to think about all the pain and destruction he has caused in the earth. But most importantly, the universe gets to see all the pain and suffering that sin causes. He claimed to the angels in heaven that his way of handling things was superior to God's. He said to the angels that He would make the fairer ruler. Satan and his true character will be fully unmasked at the end of the thousand years."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"When are the rest of the unrighteous dead raised?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 20:5","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":5}]},"note":{"text":"Those that were destroyed by the brightness of His coming as well as those who were in the graves are now raised at the end of the millennium."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What are God's people doing during the 1000 years?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 20:4-6; 1 Cor. 6:2, 3","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":4,"verseEnd":6},{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":6,"verseStart":2,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"There will be many unanswered questions when we arrive in heaven with Christ. In his great love and compassion God has set aside 1000 years to answer all our questions. It's important to God that we understand and be included in this important judgment of those who rejected Christ (including Satan and his angels)."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What happens to Satan and his angels at the end of the 1000 years?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 24:19-23; Rev. 20:7","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":24,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":23},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What does Satan do that clearly shows that he has not changed?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 20:7-9","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":9}]},"note":{"text":"Satan is bound exactly the same amount of time that the lost are dead and he will be loosed exactly when the lost are resurrected but only for a short time. Wherever they were slain on the earth they are raised to life. They continue under Satan's deception as they did during their lifetime and are ready to do his bidding now as always."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What occurs just before the eternal death of the unrighteous?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 20:11-13","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":11,"verseEnd":13}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"Why are the unbelievers brought back to life?","scripture":{"raw":"Jude 14, 15","refs":[{"book":"Jude","chapter":1,"verseStart":14,"verseEnd":15}]},"note":{"text":"God desires that the unbelievers see that it was only their rejection of Christ that caused them to be lost, nothing else. God, in fact is actually on trial in a way because He desires to prove to the entire universe that Satan's accusations against Him has always been and always will be false. God has to prove that he is just for the rest of the universe. It was doubt that caused sin in the first place and God cannot ever risk sin in His universe again."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"How will God completely stop Satan's assault on the Holy City?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 20:9","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":20,"verseStart":9}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"What will happen to the earth once Satan and his army is no more?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Peter 3:13; Rev. 21:1-8","refs":[{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":3,"verseStart":13},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":21,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":8}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"In this chapter of Revelation is one of the most incredible descriptions of the final events of earth ever told. As we can see the fate of all is reserved for the second coming of Christ. But no one need experience the anguish of being lost. Jesus offers eternal life to everyone. \\"Come. Whoever is thirsty, let him come; and whoever wishes, let him take the free gift of the water of life\\". Rev. 22:17\\n\\nThe only reason for anybody to be lost is unbelief."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":15,"number":15,"title":"Heaven","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"God has promised in his word that Heaven is very real. God longs to have us with Him forever in this wonderful place. Many people have misconceptions about heaven. Some visualize themselves playing a harp on some celestial cloud; others walking around on streets of gold. In this lesson we will be exploring what the Bible actually teaches about Heaven.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What do we become when we believe in Jesus for our salvation?","scripture":{"raw":"John 1:12, 13","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":1,"verseStart":12,"verseEnd":13}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What does it mean to be a child of God?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 8:17; Gal 4:7","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":17},{"book":"Galatians","chapter":4,"verseStart":7}]},"note":{"text":"An heir is usually a son or daughter that will one day inherit all that the father and mother own. If you are an heir of God and if Jesus is now your brother than this status is elevated to you in Heaven. Everything that Jesus is promised belongs to you as well. What an incredible thought!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What is promised to Jesus, our brother, and to us as sons and daughters of God?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 1:2","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":1,"verseStart":2}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What did Christ promise He would prepare for his followers?","scripture":{"raw":"John 14:1-3","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"Imagine the Son of God excitedly getting everything ready for us. When we have guests we like to make certain everything is nice for them. In the same way, Jesus is busy making sure that everything is perfect for us. He is preparing for His bride with which he is madly in love."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"How does the Bible describe the place that God is preparing for us?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Cor. 2:9","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":2,"verseStart":9}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What type of place is this to be?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 11:10, 16","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":11,"verseStart":10},{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":11,"verseStart":16}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What is the name of this heavenly city?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 21:2","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":21,"verseStart":2}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"How does the Bible describe the New Jerusalem?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 21:17-25","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":21,"verseStart":17,"verseEnd":25}]},"subParts":["a. Verse 18 - The wall of it was of ___","b. Verse 18 - The city was pure ___","c. Verse 21 - The twelve gates were twelve ___","d. Verse 21 - The streets were pure ___","e. Verse 23 - The city needed neither ___","f. Verse 25 - There shall be no ___"]}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What planet is to be the eternal home of God's children?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 5:5","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":5,"verseStart":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"From where did John say the New Jerusalem would come to this earth?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 21:2, 3, 10","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":21,"verseStart":2,"verseEnd":3},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":21,"verseStart":10}]},"note":{"text":"New Jerusalem will be the capital city on earth and the earth will now become the center of the entire universe. Imagine the planet that rebelled against the Lord will now be elevated to the command center of the entire universe and God share His throne with us."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"How will the earth be purified to receive this beautiful city?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Peter 3:10-12","refs":[{"book":"2 Peter","chapter":3,"verseStart":10,"verseEnd":12}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How will the new earth differ from our earth today?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 21:1; Isaiah 35:1; Isaiah 60:18; Isaiah 65:25; Rev. 7:16","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":21,"verseStart":1},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":35,"verseStart":1},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":60,"verseStart":18},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":65,"verseStart":25},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":7,"verseStart":16}]},"subParts":["a. Rev. 21:1","b. Isaiah 35:1","c. Isaiah 60:18","d. Isaiah 65:25","e. Rev. 7:16"]}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"What does God promise He will do for those in heaven with him?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 21:4","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":21,"verseStart":4}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"What will be our status in Heaven?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 3:21","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":3,"verseStart":21}]},"note":{"text":"It would have been fair enough if through the death of Christ our planet would have been restored to its original place in the Universe. However, God elevates us much higher than if we would have never sinned. He \\"makes it up to us\\" for all the suffering and pain we endured and allows us to co-reign with Him. He even gives us crowns to wear in order to represent our new status as kings. When it says, \\"King of kings and Lord of lords\\" it is now evident that we are those other kings. What amazing love for us is revealed here from our God!"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"What are some of the things that we will be doing in heaven?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 65:17-22","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":65,"verseStart":17,"verseEnd":22}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":16,"text":"What will our bodies be like?","scripture":{"raw":"Phil. 3:20, 21","refs":[{"book":"Philippians","chapter":3,"verseStart":20,"verseEnd":21}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":17,"text":"What was Christ's body like?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 24:36-43","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":24,"verseStart":36,"verseEnd":43}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":18,"text":"What will happen to family ties?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 65:23; Isaiah 66:22","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":65,"verseStart":23},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":66,"verseStart":22}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":19,"text":"Will we continue to worship God on the Sabbath day?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 66:23","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":66,"verseStart":23}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"How great is God's love that the planet that sinned and crucified Him will now become the center of the entire universe and that we will reign with Him on His very throne. He loves us so much that He wants to be with us for all eternity. As we continue to find out just how much God loves us, we continue to grow in our love and trust in Him."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":16,"number":16,"title":"Why God Allows Suffering","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Suffering! It's all around us in the area of violence and abuse, divorce and war, natural disasters and disease. And bewildered millions want to know why?\\nWe gasp at the wreckage of a tornado and the broken bodies scattered about. We walk through a hospital corridor and see the faces of fear and misery. We shed tears over loved ones we have lost. It takes a strong heart not to cry out, \\"If God is a God of love, why is there so much suffering? Why doesn't He do something to stop it?\\" Once again His word contains the answers.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"Who did Jesus say was responsible for this woman's illness?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 13:16","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":13,"verseStart":16}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"Who gave Paul his 'thorn in the flesh'?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Corinthians 12:7-10","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":12,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":10}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What are the two reasons given why Paul should not have this problem removed?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Corinthians 12:7-10","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":12,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":10}]},"subParts":["a.","b."]}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Did these Galileans suffer this calamity because they were worse sinners than others?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 13:1-3","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":13,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"Was the blind man born blind because of sins he and/or his parents committed?","scripture":{"raw":"John 9:1-3","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":9,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"\\"It was generally believed by the Jews that sin is punished in this life. Every affliction was regarded as the penalty of some wrongdoing, either of the sufferer himself or his parents. It is true that all suffering results from the transgression of God's law but this truth had become perverted. Satan, the author of sin and all its results, had led men to look upon disease and death as proceeding from God; as punishment arbitrarily inflicted on account of sin. Hence one upon whom some great affliction or calamity had fallen had the additional burden of being regarded as a great sinner.\\" Desire of Ages, p. 471. This was the main reason why Jesus did so much healing. He wanted to dispel this error and show the mercy and compassion of God on all suffering humanity. Satan causes suffering but God can allow or overrule for purposes of mercy."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What did God promise Adam and Eve that He would do?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 3:15","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":3,"verseStart":15}]},"note":{"text":"\\"I will put enmity between you (serpent) and the woman. He (woman's seed) shall crush your head, and you shall strike His heel\\". (NKJV or KJV)"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"To who did the expression 'her seed' refer?","scripture":{"raw":"Gal. 3:16","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":3,"verseStart":16}]},"note":{"text":"Because of the promise that God had made, there is always a conflict between Satan (the prince of this world) and those who follow Christ. The real conflict was magnified with Christ shown as bruising the serpent's head (destroying Satan) and Satan bruising Christ's heel (causing suffering). It was God's plan to come and offer Himself up for a sacrifice for us all. Some question why God did not destroy Satan as soon as he rebelled. There was no way to explain sin to a universe that had never experienced it, and God would not, could not have a kingdom in which His subjects served Him from fear instead of love. So He had no alternative. The plan of rebellion must grow until all could see the kind of fruit it bore."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What one word best describes God's character?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 4:8","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":4,"verseStart":8}]},"note":{"text":"Whenever the bible talks about the love of God, it specifically uses the Greek word, 'agape'. This word is used to convey a love higher than we humans can produce on our own. The other words of love denote a brotherly love or a romantic love. (Phileos and Eros) Whenever we try to label God's love for us as a kind of human love it perverts the gospel of Christ. His love is much higher and broader than ours."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What help does God offer his followers?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Corinthians 10:13","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":10,"verseStart":13}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What is the result of trials in our lives if we are God's children?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 8:28","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":28}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What is the desired result of God's discipline in our lives?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 12:7-11","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":12,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":11}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How does God relate to our suffering?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 25:31-45; Acts 9:1-5","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":25,"verseStart":31,"verseEnd":45},{"book":"Acts","chapter":9,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"What assurance will help our faith to remain strong?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 8:35,38,39","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":35},{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":38,"verseEnd":39}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Not only does God set limits beyond which Satan cannot go, and promises us power and help from heaven, but He also assures us that from our ordeal He will work ultimate good. We may not understand how this can be, but in the hereafter it will become clear. Even in this life we may often see God's hand in our trials. It is God's purpose to develop our character and lessons are often learned in adversity.\\n\\nYou are God's masterpiece. He has a goal and purpose for you and He uses your lifetime to produce it. Only through Christ can God make you the way He wants you to be."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":17,"number":17,"title":"God's Law of Love = Promises","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"It has been reported that there are over 3500 laws in the United States alone and yet God has boiled His law down to only 10, which are really promises of His faith. The moral fabric of our society is unraveling quickly as situation ethics and political correctness hurtle to the forefront. We have taken prayer out of schools and wonder why kids are shooting other kids. We have taken Christ out of Christmas and wonder why greed and materialism are on the rise. And we have taken God's law from our society and wonder why our culture is crumbling into chaos with sexual perversion and violence. In this lesson we shall explore God's law and as surrendered Christians how we are to relate to them.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"Who wrote the Ten Commandments?","scripture":{"raw":"Exodus 31:18","refs":[{"book":"Exodus","chapter":31,"verseStart":18}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What is promised to those who love God's 10 Promises?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 112:1-3","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":112,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What was the conclusion of King Solomon, the wisest king who ever lived?","scripture":{"raw":"Ecclesiastes 12:13,14","refs":[{"book":"Ecclesiastes","chapter":12,"verseStart":13,"verseEnd":14}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"How does God describe King David?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 13:21, 22","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":13,"verseStart":21,"verseEnd":22}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What was David's attitude towards God's law?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 119:166-168","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":119,"verseStart":166,"verseEnd":168}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What did Paul say about God's law?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 7:12","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":7,"verseStart":12}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"When Christ came to this world, did He come to abolish the law?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 5:17-18","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":5,"verseStart":17,"verseEnd":18}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What was His attitude towards those who broke the Law and taught others to do the same?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 5:19","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":5,"verseStart":19}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What did Jesus say about those who obey the word of God?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 11:28","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":11,"verseStart":28}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What did Jesus say we are to do if we love Him?","scripture":{"raw":"John 14:15, 21, 23, 24, 15:10","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":15},{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":21},{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":23,"verseEnd":24},{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":10}]},"note":{"text":"The law is not a method for salvation rather it is the standard for Christian behavior. The law reveals what the character of our God is."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What is the sinful mind's response to God's law?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 8:7","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":8,"verseStart":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How then can we obey God's law?","scripture":{"raw":"Ezekiel 36:25-27","refs":[{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":36,"verseStart":25,"verseEnd":27}]},"note":{"text":"When Jesus lives in our hearts He will keep the commandments in us."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"What will be our response to God's law when we allow His Spirit to control us?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 119:20","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":119,"verseStart":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"How did Jesus sum up the Law and Prophets?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 22:37-40","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":22,"verseStart":37,"verseEnd":40}]},"note":{"text":"The first four commandments show our supreme love to God. The last six commandments show our love to our neighbor. When any of these are disregarded, we are showing our disrespect for either God or neighbor."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"How is love to God displayed?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 5:3","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":5,"verseStart":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":16,"text":"What is evident of those who say they love God and do not obey?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 2:3-5","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":2,"verseStart":3,"verseEnd":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":17,"text":"How are God's people described in the last days?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 12:17; Rev. 14:12","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":12,"verseStart":17},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":12}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":18,"text":"Did Jesus commission His believers to teach people to obey everything He commanded us?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 28:20","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":28,"verseStart":20}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Try reading the ten commandments with the thought of them being promises of God to you. Then it will sound like this: Exodus 20:1-17\\n\\"And God spake all these words, saying, I am the LORD thy God, which have brought thee out of the land of Egypt, out of the house of bondage. Thou shalt have no other gods before me.\\"\\nIn other words, God promises us that when we truly know His character, we will not worship any other gods. You will not want any other God but Him. He believes it, He promises it. Go ahead and read through all of them now. Enjoy those promises."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":18,"number":18,"title":"The Sabbath","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"As we studied a previous lesson we learned that the way of salvation comes only through Jesus Christ. Jesus' perfect righteousness becomes ours by believing Him and accepting His gift. God has given us a special symbol that reflects not only His Creator-ship but also His special relationship with us. In this lesson we will explore what the Bible teaches on this very important topic.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"Why did God bless the seventh day and make it holy?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 2:1-3","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":2,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"God blessed the seventh day so that it would be a blessing to His creatures then He made it holy. In other words, God proclaimed the seventh day to be a special day to continually remind man of his beginnings, his roots. God created the world in six days and then rested on the seventh day. Notice the Jewish nation had not yet been formed. God created the entire human race at this time."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What day was mankind created?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 1:26-31","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":1,"verseStart":26,"verseEnd":31}]},"note":{"text":"God created everything else before He created man. The creation of God was a gift to Adam. Adam celebrated with God in His creation by resting or keeping that day holy. Adam did not help God with creation. However, they celebrated together by resting on the seventh day. Notice that this was God's seventh day but it was man's first day. Man began his existence by resting in the perfect and holy gift of God's creation."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What significance is the Sabbath upon God's creation?","scripture":{"raw":"Exodus 20:8-11","refs":[{"book":"Exodus","chapter":20,"verseStart":8,"verseEnd":11}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Does God ever change His laws or covenants?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 89:34","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":89,"verseStart":34}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"Did Jesus ever change God's law?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 5:17, 18","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":5,"verseStart":17,"verseEnd":18}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"For whom did Jesus say the Sabbath was created?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 2:27","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":2,"verseStart":27}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What was Jesus' relationship to the Sabbath?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 12:8","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":12,"verseStart":8}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What day did Jesus die for us on?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 23:52-56","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":23,"verseStart":52,"verseEnd":56}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus died on 'preparation day' commonly referred to it as 'Good Friday'. Jesus completed our salvation, a complete and perfect work on the sixth day just as God as our Creator also completed His creation for us on the sixth day."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What day was Jesus resurrected?","scripture":{"raw":"John 20:1, 2","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":20,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":2}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus was resurrected on the first day or what we call \\"Easter Sunday\\". Just as God rested on the seventh day after His complete and perfect work of creation, God as Jesus once again rested on the seventh day after His complete and perfect work of salvation. Just as God gave us creation as a gift once again God gives us salvation as a gift of which we had no work or effort in helping God with."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What day does the Bible call Sabbath?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 23:54; Luke 24:1","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":23,"verseStart":54},{"book":"Luke","chapter":24,"verseStart":1}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"According to the Bible, what time does the Sabbath begin?","scripture":{"raw":"Genesis 1:5, 8, 13, 19, 23, 31; Lev. 23:32","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":1,"verseStart":5},{"book":"Leviticus","chapter":23,"verseStart":32}]},"note":{"text":"According to God, evening and then morning constitute a day. The setting of the sun ushers in a new day to God. Therefore the Sabbath begins at sunset on Friday evening and commences at sunset on Saturday night."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"According to the Bible, what does the observance of the Sabbath day also indicate?","scripture":{"raw":"Ezekiel 20:12, 19, 20","refs":[{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":20,"verseStart":12},{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":20,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"What did God want us to call the Sabbath?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 58:13, 14","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":58,"verseStart":13,"verseEnd":14}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"Did Jesus keep the Sabbath day holy?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 4:16","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":4,"verseStart":16}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"What about after Jesus' death? What day did the disciples keep holy?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 13:42-44","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":13,"verseStart":42,"verseEnd":44}]},"note":{"text":"The same day that was Sabbath at creation is the same day we call Sabbath today. Any calendar will tell us that Saturday is the seventh day of the week. Any dictionary will tell us that Saturday is the seventh day of the week. If the Sabbath day had been lost between Moses' time and Jesus' time, Christ would surely have set the record straight."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":16,"text":"Did Jesus think His followers would continue to keep the Sabbath after His death?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 24:20","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":20}]},"note":{"text":"If God changed the day of worship from Sabbath to Sunday why would He be concerned about the Sabbath 40 years after His death when Jerusalem was destroyed?"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":17,"text":"How did we start worshipping on Sunday instead of Saturday?","scripture":{"raw":"","refs":[]},"note":{"text":"Constantine the Great was emperor of Rome who joined the church and became a bishop. He enacted a law that first enjoined Sunday keeping in 321 A.D.\\n\\nThe earliest recognition of the observance of Sunday as a legal duty is a constitution of Constantine in 321 A.D., enacting that all courts of justice, inhabitants of towns, and workshops were to be at rest on Sunday, with the exception in favor of those engaged in agricultural labor. Encyclopedia Britannica 11th edition, \\"Sunday\\"\\n\\nAfter this, other ordinances came in through human instrumentality. Most people today do not even realize that they are following a man made law first enacted in the fourth century. Is it any wonder that God said \\"Remember the Sabbath\\"?"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":18,"text":"Is the Sabbath blessing for us today?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 4:4-9","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":4,"verseStart":4,"verseEnd":9}]},"note":{"text":"The Hebrew word \\"Sabbath\\" is translated into English by the word \\"rest\\". When we enter into God's rest by faith, we strengthen that relationship by keeping holy God's seventh day."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":19,"text":"What does Jesus say we should do if we love Him?","scripture":{"raw":"John 14:15","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":14,"verseStart":15}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"The Sabbath is a sign to His people that they may know that it is He who makes them holy. Not only is He their Creator but Savior. We rest in the perfect and complete creation and salvation that God has done for us. God did not alter or change the fourth commandment. In fact He says that if you love me, you will obey my commandments. He wants to have a special time with us each week so He can pursue a loving relationship with us. He longs to be our Savior and friend!"}}],"pageCount":4},{"id":19,"number":19,"title":"Why So Many Denominations?","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"In John 17:21 Jesus prayed for unity of his believers. He prayed that we might be one in Him just as He is one with the Father. He prayed that we might be one so that the world may believe that Jesus was sent of God.\\n\\nBut are we one? Why are there so many different denominations within the Christian faith? With so many to choose from, it can be confusing to make a decision about which to belong to. If the church is His body of believers then what has happened to divide it so?\\n\\nThe disciple John wrote the book of Revelation while a prisoner on the island of Patmos. The word revelations means to \\"reveal\\" and its' author is Jesus according to the first verse of the book. In this study we will be concentrating on the 6th chapter of Revelation.","elements":[{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"readDirective","text":"READ ENTIRE CHAPTER OF REVELATION 6 FIRST"}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"Who opened the 1st seal?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 6:1","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":1}]},"note":{"text":"Who are the 'four living creatures'? The word \\"zoon\\" according to the original Greek translation means a living being. Some have felt that these were angels."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What was the color of the first horse and what did it represent?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 6:2","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":2}]},"note":{"text":"John, the revelator was in the first century church after Jesus' ascension. In the time of Christ when a victorious general came back from a battle he returned on a white horse. It was a sign of victory. White also symbolizes purity. The early church was filled with triumph and purity. It was filled with the spirit and love of Christ and the gospel spread incredibly. This period lasted from about 33AD to 99AD. The 1st seal represents the victorious church."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What was the color of the second horse and what did it represent?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 6:3, 4","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":3,"verseEnd":4}]},"note":{"text":"Satan is enraged. He desires to stop the onward march of God's army. In this next period 100 AD-323 AD is the beginning of persecution by the Roman Army. Many Christians were cast to lions while audiences jeered in entertainment. Many were butchered. But the more they were persecuted, the more the church grew. The blood of the martyrs became the seed of the gospel. Satan realized that he would have to change his strategy. And so he did..."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What was the color of the third horse and what did he represent?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 6:5, 6","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":5,"verseEnd":6}]},"note":{"text":"Paul predicted in Acts 20:28-31 that there would be a falling away from the truth of God. In this period of corruption and materialism the church is weighed in the balance and found wanting. Satan changes his strategy and introduces distortions of the truth. Pagans only half converted came into the church with their pagan practices. Christian leaders in an attempt to unite the Christian church were willing to make compromises. Major changes took place. The former truth and power of the early church were supplanted by pagan practices that continue to creep into the church during this time period from 323 AD to 538 AD. Images and statues began to surface in churches. Church councils began to take the place of the word of God. In 321 AD a civil law by Constantine the emperor proclaimed that everything be closed on the first day of the week—and 'the venerable day of the sun' be enforced. The first church Sunday law was in place by 325 AD. Eventually man's laws began to replace the laws of God. The 3rd seal represents compromise and corruption."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What did Jesus teach about the Ten Commandments?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 5:17-19","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":5,"verseStart":17,"verseEnd":19}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What did Jesus say about those who teach tradition rather than His commands?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 15:8, 9","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":15,"verseStart":8,"verseEnd":9}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What was the color of the fourth horse and what did he represent?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 6:7, 8","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":8}]},"note":{"text":"From a powerful, spirit-filled church to a church that is spiritually dead. It has compromised and come to a place where the spirit and power of God is gone. Satan has been effective in diluting the gospel. This period of time is known as the Dark Ages, the period from 538 AD to 1517 AD. This is the time when the pope becomes the emperor of Rome and has incredible power. The word of God is kept from the people and only the Roman church has access to it. Sunday keeping comes into the church in 321 AD, images and relics in 327 AD, finally purgatory and indulgences come in along with the pagan idea of the immortality of the soul and the people have no knowledge of the true gospel of Jesus anymore. Those that defy the teachings of the church were put to death. But God had a plan for his faithful followers, 'His true church'."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What is the message of the fifth seal?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 6:9-11","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":11}]},"note":{"text":"The beginning of the Reformation takes place around 1517 AD. Many faithful people of God rise up with conviction against the hypocrisies and errors in the church at this time and are martyred. John Wycliff begins to translate the Bible into the language of the people as well as the Waldensians, a group of God fearing people of France who would laboriously hand write and distribute the Bible into the streets dressed as merchants and other non-suspecting individuals. Huss and Jerome, two heroes of the reformation who will only obey what the bible teaches were later burned at the stake by the Roman church. Later in the century, Martin Luther a priest who found an old Latin Bible, discovered that salvation is not to be paid for by indulgences or in suffering for your sins in penance but by faith in the Son of God. Little by little God was at work restoring the vital truths that had long been shrouded in darkness."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What were God's disciples emphatic about?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 5:29","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":5,"verseStart":29}]},"note":{"text":"We are naturally bent toward reverencing those who are spiritual leaders rather than God Himself. Martin Luther specifically told his followers not to take his name and make a church out of the truth that God had led him to and camp around those doctrines, but did they listen? NO. Martin Luther believed in infant baptism but in 1650 the truth about full immersion baptism as taught in the scriptures came to light and Roger Williams began a church with that new truth. They later became known as the Baptists. In Proverbs 4:18 God shows us that truth is to be restored like bricks in a foundation one brick at time. If God were to show us all the truth at once it would prove to be too much for us. God restores and teaches as man can handle.\\n\\nBut here's the PROBLEM. God wants to lead all his children to stand on the shoulders of those reformers and not to reverence their leaders but to keep accepting new light as God leads. Truth is progressive. With Wycliff, we must believe in the Bible only. With Huss, obedience is to God only. With Luther, salvation is a gift from God not to be earned. With Calvin, it's a free choice. With Wesley, salvation results in a higher standard of living. From those men of God come fuller and fuller light but God never intended us to camp there but to continue to embrace new truths as he leads."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What is an identifying mark of a 'true' church?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 8:20","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":8,"verseStart":20}]},"note":{"text":"Here is one infallible standard by which all teaching, all doctrines, all religions, and all churches must be evaluated. If they are teaching any doctrine contrary to God's eternal law, the Ten Commandments, Isaiah says, 'there is no light in them.'"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What symbolism does Jesus use for His true church?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Cor. 11:2","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":11,"verseStart":2}]},"note":{"text":"God consistently uses the term woman or virgin or bride as His church. He considers Himself, the Bridegroom and His church, the bride."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How is the \\"virgin/woman\\", God's true church, characterized in Rev. 12:17?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 12:17","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":12,"verseStart":17}]},"note":{"text":"Here we find that God's true church is identified by the fact that it keeps the commandments of God. All of them even the fourth commandment, which is to honor the Sabbath day, as did His early church."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"What is the testimony of Jesus Christ?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 19:10","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":19,"verseStart":10}]},"note":{"text":"God's true church will be a church that carefully receives and studies the prophecies of the Bible. It is a church that believes in the Bible only and in following all of the Ten Commandments no matter what the outcome. It is a matter of loyalty to God rather than loyalty to man."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"We are involved in a spiritual conflict on this planet. Satan is always trying to keep us from receiving truth. He desires to hinder what God wants to accomplish. But God is ultimately in control and He directs what He will allow or not allow. Thankfully, God's word, the Bible gives us knowledge of God's will and truth. Will we obey God or man? The choice is ours."}}],"pageCount":4},{"id":20,"number":20,"title":"God's Seal and Satan's Mark","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Satan's deceptive power becomes more and more evident as we trace his efforts against God and His people. His daring attempt to destroy God's Holy Law reached its' peak in his endeavor to substitute Sunday for God's Sabbath which has fooled the majority of people. This issue is destined to become the central point of controversy in these last days when Satan is trying to deceive the \\"very elect\\". It will divide the whole world into one of two classes.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What are the two classes that will exist at the end of the world?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 13:47-49","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":13,"verseStart":47,"verseEnd":49}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"How will God's people be distinguished from the ones who didn't believe Him?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 7:1-3","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":7,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Where is the law to be written?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 10:16","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":10,"verseStart":16}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What day is the reminder of God's creative power?","scripture":{"raw":"Gen. 2:1-3","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":2,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"God is going to seal His law among His disciples on their minds. A seal represents authority. God claims authority because He is our Creator. God set up a seal or memorial of creation in the seventh-day Sabbath."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Why is the Sabbath used by God as a distinguishing sign of His true followers?","scripture":{"raw":"Ezekiel 20:12, 20","refs":[{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":20,"verseStart":12},{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":20,"verseStart":20}]},"note":{"text":"We rest on the Sabbath day as a memorial for creation and salvation. He who is the Creator is also the creator of our holiness. We have no holiness apart from God. This is in direct contrast to a religion that teaches salvation by sacraments or works. Salvation comes from grace alone (undeserved favor from God) and there is nothing we can do to earn it."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"How are the \\"saints\\" or people of God distinguished from the ones who didn't believe Him?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 14:12","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":12}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"Satan has a counterfeit for every truth that God has made known. Just as there is the Holy Trinity of the Godhead: Father, Son and Holy Spirit so Satan has an \\"unholy trinity\\" that will make its debut in the very last days. In this lesson as well as the next we will explore who and what these three are."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Describe the beast that John saw.","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 13:1, 2","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":2}]},"subParts":["Heads and horns ___ What name was on each head? ___","Resembled a: ___ Feet like a: ___","Mouth like a: ___ Who gave the beast its power? ___"]}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"Who is the dragon?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 12:9","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":12,"verseStart":9}]},"note":{"text":"In order to decipher who or what the beast is we need to study the prophecies of Daniel. Daniel is the book of the Old Testament that points to the end time prophecies and Revelation is the book in the New Testament that also points to end time prophecies. Daniel sheds light on Revelation and Revelation expands the prophecies of Daniel. They need to be studied in light of one another."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What did Daniel see come out of the sea?","scripture":{"raw":"Dan. 7:2, 3","refs":[{"book":"Daniel","chapter":7,"verseStart":2,"verseEnd":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What does a beast represent?","scripture":{"raw":"Dan. 7:17, 23","refs":[{"book":"Daniel","chapter":7,"verseStart":17},{"book":"Daniel","chapter":7,"verseStart":23}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"What does the \\"sea\\" represent?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 17:15","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":17,"verseStart":15}]},"note":{"text":"In Daniel 2, God revealed through his prophet Daniel that there would be but four great world empires. The fourth kingdom, Rome would then be divided into ten tribes. These were comprised of ancient Europe and history has confirmed this. Since Daniel 7 also tells of four successive kingdoms, it is apparent that this prophecy parallels the prophecy of Daniel 2. Because God identified the first kingdom in Daniel 2 as Babylon, we know that the other three would have to be Mede-Persia, Greece and Rome.\\n\\nThese beasts came out of the sea, or a thickly populated territory. Daniel saw a sea tossed about by a strong wind. Winds depict strife and war (Jeremiah 49:36, 37). Thus each of these nations emerges from war and strife. Isn't this usually how most nations make their debut? In contrast, the leopard-like beast of Rev. 13 came up out of the sea, but no winds were mentioned, for it was given its power from Satan."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"How many horns did this beast have?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 13:1","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":1}]},"note":{"text":"These ten horns are the same ten toes of the statue in Daniel 2 that speaks of the dividing of the empire of Rome. Ten barbarian tribes finally broke Rome's long iron rule. These ten tribes ruled for a while and three fell away entirely. The remaining seven became the forerunners of modern Europe. This is the same beast (or nation) spoken of in Daniel 2 and 7."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"What does the 'little horn' have power to do?","scripture":{"raw":"Daniel 7:19-25","refs":[{"book":"Daniel","chapter":7,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":25}]},"subParts":["\\"Eyes and mouth that spoke ___\\"","\\"Waging ___ against the ___ and ___\\"","\\"Speak against the ___\\"","\\"___ His saints\\"","\\"Try to ___ the set ___ and ___\\""]}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"introduction","text":"This power arises out of the divisions of Rome. This little horn power would be different from the first ten. They were all political powers; this would be a religious power."}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"What power sprang up from the ten tribes of early Europe and became a religious world leader? What same power persecuted the saints and thought to \\"change God's laws\\"?","scripture":{"raw":"","refs":[]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":16,"text":"What commandment deals with time?","scripture":{"raw":"","refs":[]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"The world is rapidly being arrayed under one of two banners, bearing the authority of God or Satan. To decide to be loyal is to invite opposition but the end result is inner peace and eternal life. The Bible is clear about Satan's intentions. We will discover more about this in our next lesson."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":21,"number":21,"title":"God's Warning - The Mark of the Beast","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Throughout our study of the Bible we have seen the continuing efforts of our heavenly Father to save the human race from destruction. As various times of calamity came upon the world, God sent special messages of warning and entreaty to the human race to save them from danger. Noah proclaimed God's final warning message for 120 years. Now, before the world will be cleaned by fire, can we expect a special message of pleading and warning to earth's inhabitants that will prepare a people for this great calamity? Absolutely!\\n\\nIn our last study we learned that the Sabbath is a memorial of God's creative power and that it would be a special sign or seal of His people in opposition to the mark of the beast. We also learned that there would be an \\"unholy trinity\\" that would usher in the sign of the anti-Christ or mark of the beast. So far we learned that Satan was the cornerstone of this trio and that the beast (nation) of Revelation 13 is Papal Rome. Now we will learn who or what will complete this evil plan.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"How much time was granted to the beast (papal Rome) to remain in abusive power?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 13:1-10","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"The Roman emperor Justinian, made a decree giving the papacy unlimited power over all the churches. This decree went into effect in 538 A.D. when the three opposing kingdoms were \\"pulled up by the roots\\". This began the period known as the 'dark ages'."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"How are we to interpret \\"dates and times\\" in the Bible?","scripture":{"raw":"Ezekiel 4:6","refs":[{"book":"Ezekiel","chapter":4,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"Forty-two months would be 1260 days, or years. A Jewish year contained 12 months of 30 days each, or 360 days. This same time period is also referred to in Rev.12: 5,6, 13,14. A year was sometimes called a \\"time\\", as when King Nebuchadnezzar was with the beasts of the field for \\"seven times\\" or seven years. Allowing 360 days for a \\"time\\", 720 or twice that amount for \\"times\\" and 180 days for a half of a time, it totals the same as 42 months or 1260 prophetic years. (Daniel 7:25) God wants to make it very clear who this beast power is by giving the same time clues over and over."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What happened to Rome at the end of the 42 months from 538 AD when the Pope was made king and began the most heinous of persecutions to all who opposed the Roman church?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 13:10 (NKJV)","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":10}]},"note":{"text":"In 1798 the Pope was taken prisoner by Napoleon's army. He died in the French fortress of Valence 18 months later. Therefore, he who sent others into captivity went himself into captivity. But \\"the deadly wound was to be healed\\". In 1929, the Italian government recognized Vatican City as an independent state. Papal Rome's power was reinstated and has been growing in the political arena."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Describe the beast nation that John saw coming up out of the earth.","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 13:11","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":11}]},"note":{"text":"This beast or nation comes up out of the earth- not the sea, as did the others. Therefore it must arise in a relatively un-populated area. It appears about the time (1798) when the pope is taken captive. It is a young beast unlike the other more mature beasts indicating a young nation. Only one power meets these specifications- the United States. Cradled and nourished in the wilderness of the New World, it rose to world prominence in the latter part of the eighteenth century."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What does this beast force people to do?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 13:12","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":12}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What will those who worship the beast or its image receive?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 13:15-17","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What about those who don't comply?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 13:15","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":15}]},"note":{"text":"This \\"image\\" will not be fully formed until political authority enforces religious laws to set up mandatory Sunday worship."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What is the number of the beast, the man's number?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 13:18","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":13,"verseStart":18}]},"note":{"text":"What 'man' represents the Papacy? It is none other than the office of the pope who bears the Latin title, \\"Vicarius Filii Dei\\", or \\"Vicar of the Son of God.\\"\\n\\nFollowing the ancient custom of a person having both a number and a name, let us add the Roman numerals in this title: V-5, I-1, C-100 A & R, no value, I-1, VU-5 S & F, no value I-1, L-50, I-1, I-1, D-500 E, no value, I-1. This totals 666."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What is the special message that God gives to the people in these last days?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 14:6-12","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":6,"verseEnd":12}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What is the message of the 1st angel?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 14:6, 7","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":6,"verseEnd":7}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What commandment specifically points to God as creator?","scripture":{"raw":"Exodus 20","refs":[{"book":"Exodus","chapter":20,"verseStart":8,"verseEnd":11}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"What is the application of the 2nd angel's message to the last days?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 14:8; Rev. 18:1-3, 23, 24","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":8},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":18,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]},"note":{"text":"The term 'Babylon' is derived from Babel and signifies spiritual confusion. It is used in Scripture to designate the various forms of false religion. In Rev. 17 Babylon is represented as a woman. This figure is used in the Bible as the symbol of a church. A virtuous woman represents a pure church and an evil woman represents a false church. Since this scarlet woman is sitting on the beast, it is indicative of a false church united with a nation or power. This dominant religious power has introduced a false worship system not based on God's pure gospel and was also responsible for the blood of many martyrs. This is Papal Rome."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"What does God warn against in the 3rd angel's message?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 14:9-11","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":11}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"In contrast, how are those saints described in the next verse?","scripture":{"raw":"Revelation 14:12","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":12}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"In the most startling prophecy ever the Bible predicts that church and state will unite under the banner of Satan. As calamities and disasters continue to mount one can see how the world will respond to return once again to God and with that...a mandate for total community worship...on Sunday.\\n\\nGod however will not bring the end of the world without first providing all with knowledge of His messages as well as a way of escape. With this knowledge in mind, Sabbath becomes much more than an alternative day to worship God. It becomes the symbol for loyalty to God or to Satan."}}],"pageCount":2},{"id":22,"number":22,"title":"The Meaning of the 144,000","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"As Jesus hung on the cross He was tempted three times by Satan to come down from the cross. Christ could have done this because He was God but He hung on the cross and faced this last terrible temptation. In darkness apparently forsaken of God He knew His Father's character, His justice, His mercy and His great love. It was by faith that He overcame His feelings that told Him that God had abandoned Him. He looked past circumstances and His own feelings and had total trust.\\n\\nIn the same way, just prior to the second coming of Christ, our faith will be tested to the very end. Those whose trust in God will endure the 'great tribulation' are called the \\"144,000\\" in the Bible. These represent those believers who have overcome just as Christ overcame.\\n\\nThis study will trace the experience of this group who have heard and accepted the gospel, the righteousness of Christ as presented in the three angels message and have responded to these messages in faith.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What question is asked when Jesus' second coming?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 6:12-17","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":6,"verseStart":12,"verseEnd":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What similar question does Jesus ask in this text?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 18:8","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":18,"verseStart":8}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What is the answer to the question at the end of time?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 7:1-4","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":7,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":4}]},"note":{"text":"God will have a people before the angels let go of the four winds of the earth."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"In this text what is the destroying wind a symbol of?","scripture":{"raw":"Jeremiah 49:36, 37","refs":[{"book":"Jeremiah","chapter":49,"verseStart":36,"verseEnd":37}]},"note":{"text":"Wind is a symbol of war, strife and destruction. Viewed in the light of the great controversy between Christ and Satan, these destructive forces represent the efforts of Satan to spread ruin and destruction everywhere. These angels are holding in check the plans of the enemy. They are keeping the armies of Satan at bay until the sealing of God's people shall be accomplished. When the work of sealing is completed then God will allow Satan's destructive forces to come onto the world."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"How many are sealed?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 7:4","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":7,"verseStart":4}]},"note":{"text":"This number is symbolic of the faithful found at the end of time just before Christ comes."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Are these all literally from the nation of Israel?","scripture":{"raw":"Gal. 3:26-29; Romans 2:28, 29; Romans 4:11","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":3,"verseStart":26,"verseEnd":29},{"book":"Romans","chapter":2,"verseStart":28,"verseEnd":29},{"book":"Romans","chapter":4,"verseStart":11}]},"note":{"text":"A believer is a 'spiritual' Jew according to the Bible. Thus these 144,000 refer to a group that is described in symbolic terms. The number \\"12\\" in the Bible refers to perfection or completion. 12 tribes of Israel, 12 disciples, etc. Therefore 12 x12 =144. The thousand is for emphasis that would be ultimate completion or perfection."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What does the Bible call this period of time?","scripture":{"raw":"Daniel 12:1; Rev. 12:12","refs":[{"book":"Daniel","chapter":12,"verseStart":1},{"book":"Revelation","chapter":12,"verseStart":12}]},"note":{"text":"When God's people are completely sealed with His Spirit and are prepared to stand during this difficult time then He will allow this terrible time to begin."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What will happen to God's people during this time?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 14:12","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":12}]},"note":{"text":"They will endure the strife and confusion during this time of the mark of the beast time of trouble. They will remain faithful to God and to His commandments."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"Where will God be for us at this time?","scripture":{"raw":"Isaiah 41:17, 10","refs":[{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":41,"verseStart":17},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":41,"verseStart":10}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What description is given of the 144,000?","scripture":{"raw":"Rev. 14:1-5","refs":[{"book":"Revelation","chapter":14,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":5}]},"note":{"text":"This group has the Father's name written on their foreheads. They are sealed in their minds and have settled into the truth so that they cannot be shaken from it. They are also described in symbolic language as virgins."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"What does \\"virgin\\" symbolize?","scripture":{"raw":"2 Corinthians 11:2","refs":[{"book":"2 Corinthians","chapter":11,"verseStart":2}]},"note":{"text":"They are totally dedicated and loyal to Christ."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"What promise does God make to His people?","scripture":{"raw":"Jude 24","refs":[{"book":"Jude","chapter":1,"verseStart":24}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"The time of trouble that will precede the second coming of Christ will be a difficult one but we shall in the end be preserved by our God who loves and strengthens us. God will seal us with His mighty spirit so that we can stand during this time. God does not give us strength until the exact moment when we need it. We can trust in Him that He will take care of us day by day as we trust in Him."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":23,"number":23,"title":"My Body - A Temple for Him?","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"The human body was created by God on the sixth day. It is marvelously made. He has provided bountifully from the things of nature for our care; and it is our pleasure to use these blessings to keep ourselves in good health so that we better understand His character and minister to those around us.\\n\\nWe can live as did Daniel, in full obedience to all of God's laws. A basic aspect of this is the diet we choose. What you put in your body affects all of your organs and tissues. A wrong diet hinders mental and physical efficiency. Eating the right amount of food, at regular hours is what is needed.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What food did the Creator originally give man to eat?","scripture":{"raw":"Gen. 1:29","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":1,"verseStart":29}]},"note":{"text":"herb bearing seed = fruit + grain\\ntrees = fruit + nuts\\nIn other words the original diet consisted of: fruit, nuts and grains."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What kind of food did God add after sin?","scripture":{"raw":"Gen 3:18","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":3,"verseStart":18}]},"note":{"text":"God in His great love added vegetables after sin had entered. (the herb of the field). It is interesting to note that vegetables contain much more anti oxidants (anti cancer agents) than fruits in order to prevent disease that now had access to human kind. Meat was not included in man's diet until after the Flood since there was no other source of food after exiting the arch."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"In what two categories did God divide the animals that went into the arc?","scripture":{"raw":"Gen 7:2","refs":[{"book":"Genesis","chapter":7,"verseStart":2}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"How can we determine if an animal is clean or unclean?","scripture":{"raw":"Deut 14:6 (Leviticus chapter 11)","refs":[{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":14,"verseStart":6}]},"note":{"text":"Most of the sea animals that are prohibited are the garbage eaters or scavengers of the ocean. Pigs are scavengers also. In fact, a high percentage of human bodies autopsied are infected with trichinae.\\n\\nWhen the SDA church first began in the mid 1850's their workers were often getting sick and dying young. The diet in general back in those days was pretty bad. While in prayer God seemed to be directing them to the health principles that were in the Bible. As a result the church today operates the largest hospital health care system in the world. When compared to the rest of the Christian community, results show that Adventist men live 8.9 years longer and women 7.5 years longer even though this is not our reason for eating healthy. We desire a better understanding of the One who loves us more than He loves Himself. It is always wise to follow God's principles for living a more abundant and healthy life."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"Did Daniel keep his body pure?","scripture":{"raw":"Daniel 1:8","refs":[{"book":"Daniel","chapter":1,"verseStart":8}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Why should we be careful in caring for our bodies?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Corinthians 3:16-20","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":3,"verseStart":16,"verseEnd":20}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"list","title":"NEWSTART","text":"There is more to good health than just diet. \\"Pure air, sunlight, temperance, rest, exercise, proper diet, the use of water, trust in divine power, these are the true remedies.\\" Ministry of Healing p. 127\\n\\nThere is a way to remember those principles: It's the word NEWSTART","items":["N - Nutrition (diet)","E - Exercise (a 20 minute walk can do wonders)","W - Water (8 glasses per day will refresh and clean your system beautifully)","S - Sunlight (20 min of sun exposure produce Vitamin D that can not be produced any other way, it also kills germs)","T - Temperance (One can even overdue the \\"good thing\\" :-)","A - Air (Open your windows for 20 minutes each day to aerate your house)","R - Rest (8-10 hours a night are ideal. The hours before midnight count double)","T - Trust in Divine Power (Know that He has redeemed you and loves you with an everlasting love)"]}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What does the Bible teach about alcoholic beverages?","scripture":{"raw":"Proverbs 20:1; Proverbs 23:29-33","refs":[{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":20,"verseStart":1},{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":23,"verseStart":29,"verseEnd":33}]},"note":{"text":"Research has clearly demonstrated that even \\"moderate\\" drinking destroys thousands of brain cells. It affects conscience, reason and judgment and we need to keep it clear for it is through our mind that God speaks to us."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What principle may be applied in all matters of health and Christian living?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Corinthians 6:19, 20; 1 Corinthians 10:31","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":6,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":20},{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":10,"verseStart":31}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What mistake did the Pharisees make regarding health practices and customs?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 23:23, 24","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":23,"verseStart":23,"verseEnd":24}]},"note":{"text":"They were more concerned with these outward practices than with their relationship to God and to others. They would meticulously 'strain out a gnat' in their food to avoid eating it but Jesus considered their sinful, prideful ways as likened to 'swallowing a camel'."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"There are two principles here. One is that whatever you do you do it for the glory of God. The other is falling into the trap of concentrating on external habits and practices to the exclusion of \\"heart matters\\". God will continue to convict and guide you in your relationship with Him. Your part is to allow Him to lead."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":24,"number":24,"title":"Ambassadors For Christ","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Once we accept Christ, we are called 'ambassadors for Christ'. The American ambassador represents the United States in foreign countries. We, as Christ's ambassadors, represent our future home--heaven. As such, we are walking witnesses to God's presence in our lives. People will see 'Christ' in us. Let's explore what God's principles of living are and how we relate to them.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What does Paul advice the believers in Corinth to do?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 12:2","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":12,"verseStart":2}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What does John teach regarding 'the world'?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 2:15","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":2,"verseStart":15}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What are the three areas that John specifically tells to guard against?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 2:16","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":2,"verseStart":16}]},"subParts":["1.)","2.)","3.)"],"note":{"text":"Worldliness is anything that is motivated by self-interest. Our motivation is important to God and is at the center of what we do."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Is 'worldliness' a trait of only the non-believer?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Corinthians 3:1-3","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":3,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":3}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What are some other evidences of having a sinful nature or living 'in the world'?","scripture":{"raw":"Gal. 5:19-21","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":5,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":21}]},"note":{"text":"Sanctification or being made 'holy' by God is a process and takes time. In this passage Paul is addressing the Corinthian church that He brought to Christ ten years earlier. He is telling them that by now they should have grown into mature Christians."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"How does one grow into a mature Christian?","scripture":{"raw":"Gal. 5:16-18","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":5,"verseStart":16,"verseEnd":18}]},"note":{"text":"One 'lives by the Spirit' by keeping a close connection with God through prayer, reading His words and surrendering our hearts and lives to Him on a daily basis. It is only then that the Spirit continues His work in us."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What are some of the attributes of the Spirit living within us?","scripture":{"raw":"Gal. 5:22-25","refs":[{"book":"Galatians","chapter":5,"verseStart":22,"verseEnd":25}]},"note":{"text":"The Bible has many admonitions for the believer. Many of these were in the framework of the culture of those days. For instance in 1 Tim. 2:8-10, it is written that women should not braid their hair. What is the harm in that? In the days of Paul only prostitutes braided their hair and wore extensive jewelry. In essence, what Paul is saying is that God's children should not dress like prostitutes. So, rather than giving 'rules' it is better to give 'principles'. A principle transcends culture and time. It cuts right to the heart of the matter. In this lesson we will be looking at five basic principles."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"principle","title":"FIVE BASIC PRINCIPLES FOR CHRISTIAN LIVING","text":"","items":["1. MOTIVATION- Why are you doing it? Who gets the glory out of it? 2 Cor. 5:14, 15","2. RELATIONSHIP- You put others and their needs above yours. 1 Cor. 10:24; 1 Cor. 9:22","3. PRIORITIES- What is more important: the outward or the inward? Do we spend more time on the outward adornment or on the inward in cultivating a godly spirit? 1 Tim. 2:8-10; Col. 3:1, 2; 1 Peter 3:3,4","4. CONSISTENCY- Are we consistent in our behavior? Are we dependable to others? Do we say one thing and do another? Matthew 23:1-3","5. SIMPLICITY- Not being encumbered with the abundance of possessions but with the simplicity of a beautiful inner spirit. Luke 12:15"]}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"It is the work of God to make us ambassadors for Christ. Our part is only always to keep coming to Him, for love, for confession, for forgiveness and for grace strength and power. He then continues to work in us so that others may see Him in us and be drawn to Him. In exchange we live full, abundant purposeful lives which touches and blesses many especially ourselves."}}],"pageCount":2},{"id":25,"number":25,"title":"God With Us in Our Finances","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"There is more written in the book of Proverbs about money than any other subject. It can prove to be a blessing in our lives or a snare to us. And it's our attitude toward it that determines how we use it in this life.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"To whom, do we, our possessions, and the earth belong?","scripture":{"raw":"Psalm 24:1, 2","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":24,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":2}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"Who gives us the ability to get wealth?","scripture":{"raw":"Deut. 8:18; 1 Chron. 29:12","refs":[{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":8,"verseStart":18},{"book":"1 Chronicles","chapter":29,"verseStart":12}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"What is God's advice in our attitude towards money?","scripture":{"raw":"Prov. 11:28; Psalm 49:16-20; Luke 12:15-21; 1 Tim. 6:17-19","refs":[{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":11,"verseStart":28},{"book":"Psalms","chapter":49,"verseStart":16,"verseEnd":20},{"book":"Luke","chapter":12,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":21},{"book":"1 Timothy","chapter":6,"verseStart":17,"verseEnd":19}]},"note":{"text":"All our money and possessions belong to God and it is He who gives it to us. He wants us to trust in Him to provide for our needs not in ourselves."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Can money become a snare with which we are tempted? In what way?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Tim. 6:6-10","refs":[{"book":"1 Timothy","chapter":6,"verseStart":6,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"It is easy to fall into the trap of pursuing money to the exclusion of everything else in our life. Many people live as though money were the chief concern in this world. And eventually everything else gets crowded out especially our trust in God. This is one thing we must guard against."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"How does God address this problem to us?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 12:22-34","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":12,"verseStart":22,"verseEnd":34}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"What should be our attitude toward money with relation to others?","scripture":{"raw":"Prov. 11:25, 26; Luke 6:38","refs":[{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":11,"verseStart":25,"verseEnd":26},{"book":"Luke","chapter":6,"verseStart":38}]},"note":{"text":"The world says to hold on to as much as possible, but God blesses those who give freely of their possessions, time and energy. When we give, God supplies us with more so that we can give more. In addition, giving helps us gain a right perspective on our possessions. We realize they were never really ours to begin with, but they were given to us by God to be used to help others."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"Should we store up for the future?","scripture":{"raw":"Proverbs 21:20","refs":[{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":21,"verseStart":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What about countersigning for another?","scripture":{"raw":"Proverbs 17:18; Proverbs 22:26, 27","refs":[{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":17,"verseStart":18},{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":22,"verseStart":26,"verseEnd":27}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"Should we lend to others who ask us?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 6:34, 35; Deut. 15:7, 8, 10, 11","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":6,"verseStart":34,"verseEnd":35},{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":15,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":8}]},"note":{"text":"The money we decide to give to others should be considered as a gift; not a loan. Therefore we should make sure that we can afford to give such a gift in case there is no repayment."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What should be our attitude toward money in relation to God?","scripture":{"raw":"Psa 96:8; Prov. 3:9, 10","refs":[{"book":"Psalms","chapter":96,"verseStart":8},{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":3,"verseStart":9,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"The 'first fruits' refers to the practice of giving to God's use the first and best portion of the harvest. (Deuteronomy 26:9-11). Many people give God their leftovers. If they can afford to donate anything, they do so. These people may be sincere and contribute willingly, but their attitude is nonetheless backward. We need to give God the first part of our income. This demonstrates that God, not possessions, have first place in our lives and that our resources belong to him and that we are only managers of God's resources. Giving to God first helps us to conquer greed, helps us properly manage God's resources, and opens us up to receive God's special blessings."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"How much does God consider the 'first fruit'?","scripture":{"raw":"Deut. 14:22, 23","refs":[{"book":"Deuteronomy","chapter":14,"verseStart":22,"verseEnd":23}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"What does God promise if we return tithe to Him?","scripture":{"raw":"Malachi 3:6-10","refs":[{"book":"Malachi","chapter":3,"verseStart":6,"verseEnd":10}]},"note":{"text":"The people of Malachi's day ignored God's promise of blessings. They may have feared losing what they had worked so hard to get, but in this they misjudged God. 'Give, and it will be given to you,' He says in Luke 6:38. When we give, we must remember that the blessings God promises are not always material but He always keeps His word."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":13,"text":"For what purpose was the tithe to be used during the days of ancient Israel?","scripture":{"raw":"Num. 18:21, 23, 24","refs":[{"book":"Numbers","chapter":18,"verseStart":21},{"book":"Numbers","chapter":18,"verseStart":23,"verseEnd":24}]},"note":{"text":"When Joshua led the Israelites into the Promised Land, each tribe was given a portion of land as its inheritance. The only exception to this was the tribe of Levi. As the priests, they were to spend their full time in serving the Lord. They were given no land to farm, only cities to live in. The other eleven tribes gave one tenth of their income, or increase, to support the Levites for God's work."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":14,"text":"According to the Bible, how is the clergy to be supported today?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Corinthians 9:13, 14","refs":[{"book":"1 Corinthians","chapter":9,"verseStart":13,"verseEnd":14}]},"note":{"text":"When we give our tithe we are supporting the clergy so that the gospel of Christ can go forward. In this, we are honoring God and His work in our lives."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":15,"text":"What special promise does God make for you and your family?","scripture":{"raw":"Phil. 4:19","refs":[{"book":"Philippians","chapter":4,"verseStart":19}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"Money is NOT the root of all evil, it is the LOVE of money that is evil. Money is a necessary commodity that we all need in our life. And God blesses us with money so that we may be a channel of blessing to others. And when the funds flow freely from our hearts so will the blessings of God flow freely to us and through us."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":26,"number":26,"title":"God's Conflict Resolution","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"Conflict! It's all around us. Conflict between parent and child. Conflict between husband and wife. Conflict between friend and friend. It's a part of life. But how is the Christian supposed to deal with conflict? Is there a time when conflict is necessary and are there times when we are to steer clear of it? In this lesson we will explore what the Bible teaches about conflict and the principles surrounding it.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"What does the Bible teach regarding our relationships with others?","scripture":{"raw":"Hebrews 12:14","refs":[{"book":"Hebrews","chapter":12,"verseStart":14}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"Does that mean that we can never be angry with anyone?","scripture":{"raw":"Eph. 4:26","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":4,"verseStart":26}]},"note":{"text":"Anger is one of our human characteristics. The bible tells us that anger in and of itself is not a sin but it is what you do with it that determines what is sin or not."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"How important is it to God that you settle your differences with others?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 5:23, 24","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":5,"verseStart":23,"verseEnd":24}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"How does God wishes for me to settle my differences with others?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 17:3, 4","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":17,"verseStart":3,"verseEnd":4}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"How do I handle a situation where another believer wrongs me?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 18:15-17","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":18,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"How should handle faultfinding and having a critical attitude?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 7:1-5","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":7,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What does the Bible teach about granting forgiveness to others when they seek it from us?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 6:14, 15; Matt. 18:21, 22","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":6,"verseStart":14,"verseEnd":15},{"book":"Matthew","chapter":18,"verseStart":21,"verseEnd":22}]},"note":{"text":"When we forgive others it does not mean that we cannot talk to them about the way they dealt with us. But it does mean that we are ready to resolve the problem with them."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"Are we to \\"love our enemies\\"?","scripture":{"raw":"Luke 6:27-36; Romans 12:14-21","refs":[{"book":"Luke","chapter":6,"verseStart":27,"verseEnd":36},{"book":"Romans","chapter":12,"verseStart":14,"verseEnd":21}]},"note":{"text":"It is impossible for the \\"natural\\" man to love his enemies. But not for the children of God! We are to be 'partakers of His nature' in every way."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"How are we able to have this kind of love for others?","scripture":{"raw":"John 15:4, 5; 1 John 4:12, 13","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":15,"verseStart":4,"verseEnd":5},{"book":"1 John","chapter":4,"verseStart":12,"verseEnd":13}]},"note":{"text":"While we cannot on our own freely love and forgive others, the Holy Spirit will give us the ability to do those things that we cannot do on our own. We have just to ask Jesus for this and consider it a done deal. (Luke 11:9-13)"}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"Should you try to be a peacemaker in someone else's quarrel?","scripture":{"raw":"Proverbs 26:17","refs":[{"book":"Proverbs","chapter":26,"verseStart":17}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"Are there ever any times when it is justified to speak out against someone directly?","scripture":{"raw":"John 2:13-16","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":2,"verseStart":13,"verseEnd":16}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"God desires for us to live in peace and love with one another. This love can only come from God whose whole being is Love. His Love is yours for the asking. When we are faced with a conflict, pray and ask God for wisdom in the matter. If we have caused injury to someone, go to the individual and ask for forgiveness. If someone has harmed you then go to that person and praying beforehand, spell the problem out. Remember tact is helpful. Try to think of something positive to tell the other so that the person is not automatically put on the defense. If they ask for forgiveness, forgive them. Ask God to help you forgive them. Do not get involved in someone else's quarrel. If someone asks for advice, refer them to the appropriate Bible verses."}}],"pageCount":2},{"id":27,"number":27,"title":"Seeing God's Love in His Prophecy","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"God is desperately using every tool He has to show His never-ending Love for you. He doesn't want you to be in the dark but share His plans with you. Bible Prophecy has proven itself accurate in all it has foretold so far. We can expect all that yet remains of its predictions to transpire as well.","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"When Christ went to heaven after His resurrection, what different gifts did He give to His church?","scripture":{"raw":"Ephesians 4:7, 8, 11","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":4,"verseStart":7,"verseEnd":8},{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":4,"verseStart":11}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What were the three reasons why He gave us these gifts?","scripture":{"raw":"Ephesians 4:11-13","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":4,"verseStart":11,"verseEnd":13}]},"subParts":["1.","2.","3."]}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"How long should these gifts remain in the church?","scripture":{"raw":"Ephesians 4:13-15","refs":[{"book":"Ephesians","chapter":4,"verseStart":13,"verseEnd":15}]},"note":{"text":"All Christians agree that the gift of evangelists, pastors, teachers, and missionaries are necessary until the coming of the Lord. Why not also the gift of prophets? The text says that these gifts are needed until \\"we all come in the unity of the faith…unto a perfect man.\\" This time has certainly not come yet. Therefore the church still needs these gifts, including the gift of prophecy."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"What is Paul's counsel about how not to \\"put out the Spirit's fire\\"?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Thess 5:19, 20","refs":[{"book":"1 Thessalonians","chapter":5,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"What is his advice for us regarding prophecies?","scripture":{"raw":"1 Thess 5:21; 1 John 4:1","refs":[{"book":"1 Thessalonians","chapter":5,"verseStart":21},{"book":"1 John","chapter":4,"verseStart":1}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Why should we test prophets?","scripture":{"raw":"Matthew 24:24","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":24,"verseStart":24}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What does the Bible predict will happen in the last days before the return of Christ?","scripture":{"raw":"Joel 2:28-31","refs":[{"book":"Joel","chapter":2,"verseStart":28,"verseEnd":31}]},"note":{"text":"God says that in the last days before His return He will give prophecies and visions to His people, both men and women. Prior to the world being destroyed by a flood, God sent Noah to warn the world before it happened. Wouldn't it make sense for God to send special warnings to the world before it is ultimately destroyed by fire? But because there will be \\"false prophets\\" that will come we are told not to \\"treat prophecies with contempt\\" but to test them."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What is one of the ways we can test a prophet?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 7:15-20","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":7,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":20}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What test must be applied to a prophet's teaching and work?","scripture":{"raw":"1 John 4:2; Isa. 8:19, 20","refs":[{"book":"1 John","chapter":4,"verseStart":2},{"book":"Isaiah","chapter":8,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":20}]},"note":{"text":"According to the word of God, a true prophet must harmonize with all the law and teachings of the Bible. There have been some who have been called prophets in this last century but if his instruction is contrary to the Bible, he proves himself to be false."}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"illustration","title":"The Story of Ellen G. White","text":"In the fall of 1844, a young man by the name of Hazen Foss received what he believed to be a vision from God. Shortly afterward he was told to relate the vision to others but he was afraid to do so. He said God warned him of the consequences of not obeying and that if he refused, the light would be given to someone else. Being fearful of ridicule, he refused to relate the vision. Then, very strange feelings came to him, and a voice said, \\"You have grieved away the Spirit of the Lord.\\" Horrified at his own stubbornness and rebellion, he told the Lord that he would relate the vision, but when he assembled a company of Christian believers, he could not remember the vision. In vain were his attempts to call up the scenes as they had been shown to him; and then in deep despair he exclaimed, \\"It is gone from me; I can say nothing and the Spirit of the Lord has left me.\\" Eyewitnesses described it as the most terrifying meeting they were ever in.\\n\\nEarly in 1845, Foss overheard a young, frail 17 year old girl named Ellen Harmon relate a vision she had experienced to a company of believers at Portland, Maine. He recognized her vision as the one that had been given to him earlier. Upon meeting her the next morning, he recounted his experience and encouraged her to faithfully perform her work, stating: \\"I believe the visions are taken from me and given to you. Do not refuse to obey God, for it will be at the peril of your soul. I am a lost man. You are chosen of God; be faithful in doing your work, and the crown I might have had, you will receive.\\" On comparing dates, they discovered that it was not until after he had been told that the visions were taken from him, that Ellen was given her first revelation.\\n\\nEllen G. White was a woman who had an incredible relationship with the Lord as evidenced from her writings. It is estimated that she had approximately 2000 visions varying in length from 15 minutes to almost four hours. During a vision Mrs. White's breathing ceased entirely. Her heart and pulse continued to beat and her eyes were always open and directed upward. Until her death at 87 in 1915, this messenger of God faithfully fulfilled her work and bore the fruits of genuineness. Never in a single instance did her teachings vary from the acid test of Holy Scriptures. Her very last words uttered in a large public meeting were: \\"Brethren and sisters, I commend to you this Book [the Bible].\\" Her life and writings \\"edified\\" (built up) the church, strengthened the ministry, glorified Christ, and led to the \\"perfecting of the saints\\".\\n\\nThough only having a third grade education, she is one of the most published authors and her books have been translated into more languages than any other female author. Millions of people attest to the value of her writings in leading them closer to the Lord. Also a vast and worldwide movement embracing schools, hospitals, universities, publishing houses, and even a medical school, are the direct fruit of her life of service and her revelation from the Lord. If one applies Jesus' test to her, \\"By their fruits you shall know them,\\" he finds abundant evidence that her call was indeed a genuine one."}}],"pageCount":3},{"id":28,"number":28,"title":"Baptism","seriesName":"The Joy in the Journey Bible Study Series","introduction":"We have already learnt that we are all born in Adam. We are sinners by birth and by nature. Because of this we, of ourselves, can not change our hearts or our actions. Through the sacrifice of Christ for the whole world God has redeemed everybody. But because God created mankind with a free will, He will not force this free gift of salvation on anyone. Only those who receive His gift of salvation by faith will obtain it. The desire of baptism usually burns in the soul that has received this gift. Let's learn more about it.\\n\\nThe word, \\"baptism\\" is used 97 times in the bible. This gives us some indication of its supreme importance. But what does it mean and how does it affect us?","elements":[{"kind":"question","data":{"number":1,"text":"How important is baptism?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 16:15, 16; John 3:3-5","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":16,"verseStart":15,"verseEnd":16},{"book":"John","chapter":3,"verseStart":3,"verseEnd":5}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":2,"text":"What is the meaning of baptism?","scripture":{"raw":"Romans 6:3-5; Col. 2:12","refs":[{"book":"Romans","chapter":6,"verseStart":3,"verseEnd":5},{"book":"Colossians","chapter":2,"verseStart":12}]},"note":{"text":"When we are baptized we show that we are identifying with the death, burial and resurrection of Jesus Christ. Baptism means that we have died with Christ and buried the old self of sin and that we are rising to \\"a new life in Christ\\". The physical act of baptism graphically represents the steps of conversion. First we're lowered into the water; we are immersed completely just as people who have died are lowered into the grave and covered. This indicates that we have died with Christ and have buried our old lifestyle. Baptism is a funeral, a formal farewell to an existence where sin dominated. Then we're lifted up out of the water just like a person being resurrected from the grave. In this world we begin with life and end with death. In the spiritual, we begin with death and end with eternal life."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":3,"text":"Who is first mentioned as administering baptism in the New Testament?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 3:1-6","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":3,"verseStart":1,"verseEnd":6}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":4,"text":"Why was John the Baptist baptizing out in the wilderness?","scripture":{"raw":"John 3:23","refs":[{"book":"John","chapter":3,"verseStart":23}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":5,"text":"Why did Jesus say it was necessary for Him to be baptized?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 3:13-17","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":3,"verseStart":13,"verseEnd":17}]},"note":{"text":"Jesus was sinless. He didn't need to repent of any wrongdoing or have any guilt washed away. Christ was baptized for another reason: \\"to fulfill all righteousness.\\" By allowing John to immerse Him in the waters of the Jordan River, Jesus set a positive example for us. He identified Himself fully with us weak, sinful human beings; He was willing to take all the steps WE need to take. So when we are immersed in the waters of baptism, we are following in the steps of their Lord."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":6,"text":"Was the Father pleased when His Son, our Lord Jesus was baptized?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 1:11","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":1,"verseStart":11}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":7,"text":"What does the Bible say that indicates that Christ was baptized by immersion?","scripture":{"raw":"Mark 1:10","refs":[{"book":"Mark","chapter":1,"verseStart":10}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":8,"text":"What about the early church disciples? By what means did they baptize?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 8:36-38","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":8,"verseStart":36,"verseEnd":38}]},"note":{"text":"When we understand the true meaning of baptism, we have little difficulty recognizing the authentic form of baptism. The very word \\"baptize\\" comes from the Greek word \\"baptizo\\", and means to dip or immerse under water. For the first thirteen centuries, the almost universal practice of baptism was that of immersion. Archaeology has uncovered many baptisteries of the early church. It was not until the Council of Ravenna early in the fifteenth century that the Catholic Church accepted sprinkling as equally valid with immersion for convenience sake. Many Protestants have adopted and adapted what the Catholic Church had changed at an earlier time."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":9,"text":"What did Jesus instruct His followers to do before they baptized people?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 28:19, 20","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":28,"verseStart":19,"verseEnd":20}]},"note":{"text":"Being discipled and taught is part of the preparation for baptism. It is impossible for infants or small children to grasp the significance of salvation. A candidate for baptism is to be taught to \\"observe all things whatsoever I have commanded you.\\""}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":10,"text":"What did Peter say we are to do before we are baptized?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 2:38","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":2,"verseStart":38}]},"note":{"text":"In a total surrender of the heart to Christ, repentance comes by way of the Holy Spirit. Jesus also promises the \\"gifts\\" of the Holy Spirit to those who are baptized into Christ. The gifts of the Spirit are those special gifts that are given to you for the building up of God's kingdom. Some gifts include teaching, wisdom, hospitality, serving, giving, etc."}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":11,"text":"By what rite of passage was membership in God's church obtained?","scripture":{"raw":"Acts 2:41","refs":[{"book":"Acts","chapter":2,"verseStart":41}]}}},{"kind":"question","data":{"number":12,"text":"How important is a public confession of our faith to God?","scripture":{"raw":"Matt. 10:32, 33","refs":[{"book":"Matthew","chapter":10,"verseStart":32,"verseEnd":33}]}}},{"kind":"section","data":{"type":"conclusion","text":"In this life we need to die! The only choice we have is how. Either we die to ourselves and become alive again in Christ through baptism or we die as a sinner in Adam.\\n\\nBy dying in our place at Calvary, Jesus made a public demonstration of His love for us. We want to respond with a public demonstration of our own - an unashamed confession of our commitment to Christ through baptism."}}],"pageCount":3}]`),t={studies:e};export{t as s};
